00:00:22.620 --> 00:00:27.080
Welcome back, everyone,
and me too.

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:32.399
I just came back from Boulder
where I gave eight talks.

00:00:32.399 --> 00:00:36.180
I was on seven panels and
gave one separate

00:00:36.180 --> 00:00:39.230
talk, most on education.

00:00:39.230 --> 00:00:42.740
And one of the talks was
on teaching how to

00:00:42.740 --> 00:00:44.100
think or what to think.

00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:47.900
So there were three panelists,
one professor from Berkeley in

00:00:47.900 --> 00:00:51.640
the astronomy department, who
is also a renowned teacher,

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:54.540
and then an investigative
journalist, and then I spoke.

00:00:54.540 --> 00:00:57.590
And we all said something
for about 10 minutes.

00:00:57.590 --> 00:01:00.710
I talked about the history
of education and why it's

00:01:00.710 --> 00:01:03.310
difficult to change educational
institutions and

00:01:03.310 --> 00:01:07.630
educational practices and what
the original purposes of the

00:01:07.630 --> 00:01:11.480
schools were, so some of this
material that I'll talk about

00:01:11.480 --> 00:01:14.110
in the second to last lecture
on political barriers to

00:01:14.110 --> 00:01:17.120
educational change.

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:24.600
And I then also, before this
whole session, I described to

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:27.940
the reporter for the Daily
Camera, which is the paper in

00:01:27.940 --> 00:01:31.190
Boulder, a bit about what
I was going to say.

00:01:31.190 --> 00:01:33.790
And I talked about some of the
material I've told you already

00:01:33.790 --> 00:01:35.580
about multiplication table.

00:01:35.580 --> 00:01:39.050
So if you remember, the
multiplication table, when

00:01:39.050 --> 00:01:43.710
people get brain damage in the
arithmetic area, they can't do

00:01:43.710 --> 00:01:45.430
addition anymore, but they
can still do the

00:01:45.430 --> 00:01:47.810
multiplication table.

00:01:47.810 --> 00:01:51.210
And when people get brain damage
in the language area,

00:01:51.210 --> 00:01:54.090
they can still do addition,
but they can't do

00:01:54.090 --> 00:01:55.480
multiplication anymore.

00:01:55.480 --> 00:01:57.660
And that's because
multiplication, generally, is

00:01:57.660 --> 00:01:58.910
learned as--

00:02:06.940 --> 00:02:09.550
So when you see it, you think
of symbols and math, but

00:02:09.550 --> 00:02:12.640
actually the way most people
learn it is 6 times 9 is 54.

00:02:12.640 --> 00:02:19.270
Then you have to memorize
yet another fact.

00:02:19.270 --> 00:02:20.670
9 times 6 is 54.

00:02:20.670 --> 00:02:21.740
Oh.

00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:24.810
And then you have to learn yet
a new fact, that these two

00:02:24.810 --> 00:02:27.390
facts are related, when,
actually, if you understood

00:02:27.390 --> 00:02:29.860
the meaning, there would
be just one fact.

00:02:29.860 --> 00:02:31.020
So now you have to memorize all

00:02:31.020 --> 00:02:32.160
these linguistic sentences.

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:35.220
And no surprise, when you get
damage in the linguistic area,

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:37.580
that kind of multiplication
table goes away.

00:02:37.580 --> 00:02:39.510
So I said to the reporter, yeah,
what we really need to

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:44.720
do is teach multiplication and
math in a whole different way.

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:47.560
So the reporter, she understood
everything and

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:48.670
said, oh, that's really
interesting.

00:02:48.670 --> 00:02:50.110
I'm actually studying education

00:02:50.110 --> 00:02:52.580
myself, and I have children.

00:02:52.580 --> 00:02:55.670
And I'll try to apply that with
my children and in the

00:02:55.670 --> 00:02:56.760
teaching that I do.

00:02:56.760 --> 00:02:58.570
I said, oh, great.

00:02:58.570 --> 00:03:02.150
So then, I gave my talk, and
then the moderator asked

00:03:02.150 --> 00:03:04.570
everybody, well, does anyone
on the panel want to say

00:03:04.570 --> 00:03:06.280
anything to anybody else?

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:09.460
And so Alex Filippenko from
Berkeley, he stood up and he

00:03:09.460 --> 00:03:13.340
said, well, I agreed with
everything that Sanjoy said,

00:03:13.340 --> 00:03:16.330
except he was quoted in the
paper this morning as saying

00:03:16.330 --> 00:03:19.930
we shouldn't teach the
multiplication table.

00:03:19.930 --> 00:03:23.640
So that whole discussion, which
seemed to be completely

00:03:23.640 --> 00:03:29.140
understood, just got condensed
into one sentence.

00:03:29.140 --> 00:03:32.200
So now I didn't actually have to
say very much in response,

00:03:32.200 --> 00:03:34.320
because the second panelist,
as I mentioned, was an

00:03:34.320 --> 00:03:35.690
investigative journalist.

00:03:35.690 --> 00:03:37.900
And what she was talking about
is how you have to be very

00:03:37.900 --> 00:03:39.320
skeptical of what's
in the media.

00:03:39.320 --> 00:03:42.140
So all I had to do was look
at her for a bit, and then

00:03:42.140 --> 00:03:44.910
everybody started laughing
because the point was clear.

00:03:44.910 --> 00:03:46.920
But then I explained to
everybody else what I'd

00:03:46.920 --> 00:03:50.650
explain to the reporter.

00:03:50.650 --> 00:03:54.560
That's by way of saying that
education is a complicated

00:03:54.560 --> 00:03:58.830
subject, but the audience
understands a lot more than

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:01.820
the media does, which is one of
the barriers to political

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:04.970
change is that there's people
who understand lots of

00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:07.490
individual points, but how
do you assemble it into a

00:04:07.490 --> 00:04:09.890
coherent plan for change?

00:04:09.890 --> 00:04:12.200
Well, you need forums
for discussion.

00:04:12.200 --> 00:04:14.940
And if the reports in the media
are, oh, don't teach the

00:04:14.940 --> 00:04:17.970
multiplication table, or do
teach it but do it with lots

00:04:17.970 --> 00:04:20.709
of drill, well, it's hard to get
in a discussion of, well,

00:04:20.709 --> 00:04:23.280
actually you'd like to teach it
in a different way, where

00:04:23.280 --> 00:04:29.990
instead of memorizing this you
say, well, 6 times 9 is like 6

00:04:29.990 --> 00:04:34.630
times 10, which is 60,
minus 6, which is 54.

00:04:34.630 --> 00:04:38.090
So there's no space for putting
things like that into

00:04:38.090 --> 00:04:39.270
public discussion.

00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:41.510
And one of the purposes
of classes like

00:04:41.510 --> 00:04:45.140
this is to do that.

00:04:45.140 --> 00:04:45.710
OK.

00:04:45.710 --> 00:04:48.720
Today, we're going to talk about
lecture planning and

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:50.320
performing.

00:04:50.320 --> 00:04:54.900
What we've done so far is the
flow of the ideas in this

00:04:54.900 --> 00:04:56.185
class has gone as follows.

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:00.340
So this is a logical flow.

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:02.860
We did it slightly out of
order, because it's the

00:05:02.860 --> 00:05:04.460
preparation flow, slightly
different

00:05:04.460 --> 00:05:05.710
than the logical flow.

00:05:08.470 --> 00:05:10.710
You work out your course
goals, or even

00:05:10.710 --> 00:05:11.960
your curriculum goals.

00:05:18.590 --> 00:05:21.380
And then you decide, how are
you going to tell whether

00:05:21.380 --> 00:05:22.630
you've reached those goals?

00:05:22.630 --> 00:05:24.813
Let me just write the goal
a little clearer.

00:05:28.890 --> 00:05:30.910
And with problems, tests,
that's the way you

00:05:30.910 --> 00:05:34.860
operationalize your goals.

00:05:34.860 --> 00:05:37.320
And then given that you have
those kind of problems, well,

00:05:37.320 --> 00:05:40.610
now you have a pretty concrete
idea of what it is you're

00:05:40.610 --> 00:05:43.650
trying for, because you have
concrete examples of it.

00:05:43.650 --> 00:05:51.550
Well, lectures, recitations,
so I'll put et cetera here.

00:05:51.550 --> 00:05:55.750
What do you do with
your contact time?

00:05:55.750 --> 00:05:57.750
This is the overall structure.

00:05:57.750 --> 00:06:00.840
This is at the level where
it makes concrete sense.

00:06:00.840 --> 00:06:03.730
And this is, what do you do when
the rubber hits the road,

00:06:03.730 --> 00:06:05.330
what do you do in lecture?

00:06:05.330 --> 00:06:06.890
Last time, what we
did is we talked

00:06:06.890 --> 00:06:08.510
about interactive teaching.

00:06:08.510 --> 00:06:12.240
And there was, basically,
several time scales over which

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:14.530
you can make the class
interactive.

00:06:14.530 --> 00:06:17.770
The longest time scale was the
wood blocked example, and I'll

00:06:17.770 --> 00:06:20.980
answer a question about
that in just a moment.

00:06:20.980 --> 00:06:24.450
So now, continuing the theme of
where the rubber hits the

00:06:24.450 --> 00:06:25.840
road, today--

00:06:40.050 --> 00:06:43.230
Now that you have some
techniques, how do you

00:06:43.230 --> 00:06:44.870
assemble it into a lecture?

00:06:44.870 --> 00:06:47.910
And I use both words advisedly
and deliberately.

00:06:47.910 --> 00:06:50.010
So plan, it's essential
to plan.

00:06:50.010 --> 00:06:52.160
And performance is essential.

00:06:52.160 --> 00:06:53.660
People forget that.

00:06:53.660 --> 00:06:59.360
They forget that lecturing and
teaching is a public act, and

00:06:59.360 --> 00:07:02.080
when they forget that, the
lectures are flat.

00:07:02.080 --> 00:07:05.160
We're going to talk about the
techniques for doing that,

00:07:05.160 --> 00:07:08.110
starting with the Walter
Lewin lecture that

00:07:08.110 --> 00:07:09.890
you watched for today.

00:07:09.890 --> 00:07:12.720
Because he actually has many,
many examples, I think mostly

00:07:12.720 --> 00:07:15.470
good, of performance, and
some that I think he

00:07:15.470 --> 00:07:17.060
could improve on.

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:19.770
And we'll discuss that and work
out and induce general

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:22.230
principles that you can use.

00:07:22.230 --> 00:07:23.170
OK.

00:07:23.170 --> 00:07:24.530
Those are the questions
from last time.

00:07:24.530 --> 00:07:27.450
There was a slight review of
interactive teaching as well

00:07:27.450 --> 00:07:28.790
and things like this.

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:30.920
Now the question is, what
do you do in lecture?

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:33.030
How do you plan, and
how do you perform?

00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:35.490
And a good way to start
discussing that was actually

00:07:35.490 --> 00:07:40.980
to look at a master of the
art and see what they do.

00:07:40.980 --> 00:07:42.940
Now no master is perfect.

00:07:42.940 --> 00:07:45.580
But I think Walter Lewin did
so many things well it's

00:07:45.580 --> 00:07:48.570
really worth understanding what
he did and looking at it.

00:07:48.570 --> 00:07:52.530
So what did you notice from
your homework problem?

00:07:52.530 --> 00:07:54.690
Basically, what did you
notice that he did?

00:07:54.690 --> 00:07:57.220
And I have a bunch of
things as well.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:07:58.810
And we'll just write
them down.

00:07:58.810 --> 00:08:01.110
Because what we'll
do, as before--

00:08:01.110 --> 00:08:04.370
we've done this several times
now-- by looking at examples,

00:08:04.370 --> 00:08:07.900
we can induce general
principles.

00:08:07.900 --> 00:08:09.420
Actually, I'll leave
this here, and

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:10.670
I'll erase these guys.

00:08:17.690 --> 00:08:21.730
While I'm erasing, just pull
out your homework and the

00:08:21.730 --> 00:08:23.600
things you've noted down.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:27.830
And actually, take a minute
and check in with your

00:08:27.830 --> 00:08:31.320
neighbor and see if your
lists overlap.

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:33.740
And sort of vet your lists
with each other.

00:08:33.740 --> 00:08:35.940
And if you didn't think about
anything that could be

00:08:35.940 --> 00:08:37.799
improved, see if you can
remember anything that you

00:08:37.799 --> 00:08:39.580
would have done differently.

00:08:39.580 --> 00:08:43.010
So let's share all the points.

00:08:43.010 --> 00:08:46.090
So I can see that you've come up
with a lot of examples, and

00:08:46.090 --> 00:08:48.720
I actually had a bunch
too, because

00:08:48.720 --> 00:08:50.070
it's such a rich lecture.

00:08:50.070 --> 00:08:56.460
So let's see what things that
were done and what was either

00:08:56.460 --> 00:08:58.460
that you would keep or
you would change.

00:08:58.460 --> 00:09:02.130
And I'll put them in one or the
other side, according to

00:09:02.130 --> 00:09:04.500
how you categorize them.

00:09:04.500 --> 00:09:05.750
Any one example?

00:09:07.930 --> 00:09:08.835
Yeah, Wendy.

00:09:08.835 --> 00:09:11.174
AUDIENCE: He awards students
when something might not be

00:09:11.174 --> 00:09:12.662
intuitive for them
or something.

00:09:12.662 --> 00:09:16.878
So when he was doing analysis
of error under the square

00:09:16.878 --> 00:09:19.936
root, and he was saying, OK,
this might not be something

00:09:19.936 --> 00:09:21.094
you would know right now.

00:09:21.094 --> 00:09:23.078
I might not hold you
responsible, but it's

00:09:23.078 --> 00:09:24.580
interesting [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:24.580 --> 00:09:24.910
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:09:24.910 --> 00:09:28.030
So he tell students,
look, this is

00:09:28.030 --> 00:09:29.720
harder or not intuitive.

00:09:29.720 --> 00:09:32.420
He gives them a gauge and tells
them, look, you're don't

00:09:32.420 --> 00:09:34.200
have to worry about it before
he says something.

00:09:38.356 --> 00:09:41.580
He gives the difficulty
of something.

00:09:48.320 --> 00:09:48.860
OK.

00:09:48.860 --> 00:09:50.110
Why is that helpful?

00:09:52.720 --> 00:09:54.540
What does that do
for students?

00:09:54.540 --> 00:09:54.960
Yeah.

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:58.080
AUDIENCE: It sort of removes the
tension of thinking, oh,

00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:00.125
man, I don't know this while
they're trying to pay

00:10:00.125 --> 00:10:03.250
attention to the other
[INAUDIBLE].

00:10:03.250 --> 00:10:04.380
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:10:04.380 --> 00:10:04.590
Right.

00:10:04.590 --> 00:10:06.180
So it differentiates
the lecture.

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:09.500
So I'll put in other
color the reasons.

00:10:09.500 --> 00:10:10.570
Yeah, so it gives some kind of

00:10:10.570 --> 00:10:12.060
differentiation to the lecture.

00:10:12.060 --> 00:10:13.295
It gives a structure to it.

00:10:13.295 --> 00:10:17.850
It gives you a way of evaluating
so you know what

00:10:17.850 --> 00:10:19.430
are you supposed to be
doing here and trying

00:10:19.430 --> 00:10:20.130
to learn from it.

00:10:20.130 --> 00:10:23.930
You don't all of a sudden
trigger your reflex fear.

00:10:23.930 --> 00:10:25.260
So it minimizes fear.

00:10:30.090 --> 00:10:31.900
And it gives a clear
expectation.

00:10:31.900 --> 00:10:36.250
So in the particular lecture, he
didn't say anything was you

00:10:36.250 --> 00:10:38.440
absolutely have to know this.

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:40.930
So there wasn't a
flip example.

00:10:40.930 --> 00:10:43.850
But if it had been a flip
example, it would have the

00:10:43.850 --> 00:10:44.730
same benefit.

00:10:44.730 --> 00:10:46.990
If he said, oh, this is
really fundamental.

00:10:46.990 --> 00:10:49.500
You really, really, really,
really need to know this,

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:51.640
well, that also punctuate
the lecture.

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:54.765
So it minimize fear and
sets expectations.

00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:07.010
To expand on this point, which
is really fundamental, think

00:11:07.010 --> 00:11:09.980
about the difference between
the way a novice perceives

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:13.880
something and the way an expert
perceives something.

00:11:13.880 --> 00:11:16.060
If you want to know how a novice
perceives something,

00:11:16.060 --> 00:11:18.450
try to remember from the days
when you were not a chess

00:11:18.450 --> 00:11:19.840
Grandmaster.

00:11:19.840 --> 00:11:21.530
That shouldn't be too hard
for most of us, certainly

00:11:21.530 --> 00:11:23.310
not hard for me.

00:11:23.310 --> 00:11:25.550
You look at a chessboard,
all the moves

00:11:25.550 --> 00:11:28.630
look kind of similar.

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:30.120
Oh, I could move that pawn.

00:11:30.120 --> 00:11:31.370
You think about that
for a bit.

00:11:31.370 --> 00:11:32.440
You analyze some moves.

00:11:32.440 --> 00:11:34.670
He takes, I take, he
takes, I take.

00:11:34.670 --> 00:11:36.040
Hmm, OK, let me think about--

00:11:36.040 --> 00:11:36.643
I could move the rook.

00:11:36.643 --> 00:11:37.450
I could castle.

00:11:37.450 --> 00:11:39.460
He takes, I take, or I'll
move the bishop.

00:11:39.460 --> 00:11:41.770
And you sort of say, OK,
I'll move the bishop.

00:11:41.770 --> 00:11:44.610
That's how the novice or medium
chess player thinks,

00:11:44.610 --> 00:11:46.530
speaking from personal
experience.

00:11:46.530 --> 00:11:48.400
The way the master or the
Grandmaster looks at the

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:51.290
chessboard, the chessboard
has meaning.

00:11:51.290 --> 00:11:52.810
All the different pieces
of it are kind of

00:11:52.810 --> 00:11:54.410
talking to each other.

00:11:54.410 --> 00:11:57.710
Hmm, that pawn structures
is really full of holes.

00:11:57.710 --> 00:11:59.590
You really want to do something
about that.

00:11:59.590 --> 00:12:05.170
So the undifferentiated mass of
pieces that the notice sees

00:12:05.170 --> 00:12:07.410
is completely different from
what the expert sees, which is

00:12:07.410 --> 00:12:09.610
why the expert can remember
the chessboard

00:12:09.610 --> 00:12:13.060
and the novice can't.

00:12:13.060 --> 00:12:15.800
I noticed this exact
same thing happened

00:12:15.800 --> 00:12:16.770
in my freshman year.

00:12:16.770 --> 00:12:19.230
I learned to play bridge I'd
never played bridge before,

00:12:19.230 --> 00:12:23.540
and all my friends, who I don't
know if they did me a

00:12:23.540 --> 00:12:25.440
favor or not, taught me to play
bridge so I could play

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:26.940
bridge with them.

00:12:26.940 --> 00:12:30.360
When I first was playing with
them, at the end of the hand,

00:12:30.360 --> 00:12:31.760
everyone does the post mortem.

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:34.600
You have four people, you play
all the tricks, and everyone

00:12:34.600 --> 00:12:36.660
talks about what happened
and it didn't happen.

00:12:36.660 --> 00:12:40.850
And they would say, Oh,
yeah, why didn't you

00:12:40.850 --> 00:12:43.260
play the queen then?

00:12:43.260 --> 00:12:44.960
I was like queen of what?

00:12:44.960 --> 00:12:45.325
What queen?

00:12:45.325 --> 00:12:46.450
Did I have a queen?

00:12:46.450 --> 00:12:48.260
I didn't even remember
the cards I had.

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:49.440
I didn't even remember
how many cards

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:50.390
I had of each thing.

00:12:50.390 --> 00:12:52.810
I just sort of remembered
the last card, maybe.

00:12:52.810 --> 00:12:55.560
Or more like, oh, phew,
the hand's over.

00:12:55.560 --> 00:12:55.630
OK.

00:12:55.630 --> 00:12:58.650
I can't make anymore mistakes.

00:12:58.650 --> 00:13:00.350
That's how I would see
it compared to how

00:13:00.350 --> 00:13:01.110
they would see it.

00:13:01.110 --> 00:13:03.120
And I was like, how could they
ever even remember who had the

00:13:03.120 --> 00:13:03.890
queen of what?

00:13:03.890 --> 00:13:07.450
And by the end of, I don't know,
six months, I would say,

00:13:07.450 --> 00:13:10.370
uh, why didn't you play
the five then?

00:13:10.370 --> 00:13:12.490
Because all of a sudden,
now I was doing

00:13:12.490 --> 00:13:13.520
exactly the same thing.

00:13:13.520 --> 00:13:14.480
The hands had meaning.

00:13:14.480 --> 00:13:15.900
The cards had meaning.

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:22.240
So by doing this, by giving
clues to the difficulty or

00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:24.250
ease of things, you're actually
giving meaning.

00:13:24.250 --> 00:13:26.320
You're transferring some of that
knowledge that you have

00:13:26.320 --> 00:13:30.590
as the expert to the student,
who otherwise wouldn't know.

00:13:30.590 --> 00:13:34.510
There was another example of
that in the lecture where he

00:13:34.510 --> 00:13:37.730
said, this is the
most important

00:13:37.730 --> 00:13:39.155
equation in all of physics.

00:13:46.210 --> 00:13:50.780
He wrote that, and he boxed
it, and he said, that's

00:13:50.780 --> 00:13:52.760
probably the most important
equation in all of physics.

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:54.490
So again, he's giving something

00:13:54.490 --> 00:13:55.910
that the expert knows.

00:13:55.910 --> 00:13:58.230
Because the expert knows, oh,
yeah, when you see this,

00:13:58.230 --> 00:14:01.320
you're home free, and you know
you can model so many physical

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:02.310
systems with this.

00:14:02.310 --> 00:14:05.050
Let's tell the students how
important it is so they have

00:14:05.050 --> 00:14:07.610
some way of thinking about it.

00:14:07.610 --> 00:14:10.230
OK So that's really
fundamental.

00:14:10.230 --> 00:14:10.820
Others?

00:14:10.820 --> 00:14:12.430
Other points?

00:14:12.430 --> 00:14:13.010
Yes.

00:14:13.010 --> 00:14:17.312
AUDIENCE: He uses big ideas
and terms for them, like

00:14:17.312 --> 00:14:21.630
uncertainty and restoring
[INAUDIBLE].

00:14:21.630 --> 00:14:21.990
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:14:21.990 --> 00:14:34.800
So he uses clear terms for big
ideas, and he uses the same

00:14:34.800 --> 00:14:35.950
term each time.

00:14:35.950 --> 00:14:37.170
He's careful to do that,
so you don't

00:14:37.170 --> 00:14:38.420
wonder why it changed.

00:14:38.420 --> 00:14:45.870
How does that help students,
to give things names and

00:14:45.870 --> 00:14:46.830
repeatable names?

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:47.313
Yeah.

00:14:47.313 --> 00:14:51.660
AUDIENCE: Gives them fewer
facts to [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:51.660 --> 00:14:52.380
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:14:52.380 --> 00:14:53.880
It gives a structure
to everything.

00:14:56.560 --> 00:14:57.300
It's gone now.

00:14:57.300 --> 00:15:00.620
But it gives a structure,
repeatable abstractions that

00:15:00.620 --> 00:15:04.050
you can reuse over
and over again.

00:15:04.050 --> 00:15:05.300
Structures.

00:15:08.150 --> 00:15:09.670
In fact, it's another
example of this.

00:15:09.670 --> 00:15:10.920
It structures the knowledge.

00:15:15.170 --> 00:15:16.770
So it's structured
in his mind.

00:15:16.770 --> 00:15:17.680
He's the expert.

00:15:17.680 --> 00:15:21.770
He has a really good, sound
flexible structure.

00:15:21.770 --> 00:15:24.820
And part of the job of really
good teaching is to help the

00:15:24.820 --> 00:15:28.555
students build that structure.

00:15:28.555 --> 00:15:29.513
Yes.

00:15:29.513 --> 00:15:31.429
AUDIENCE: When he's
characterizing visions, he

00:15:31.429 --> 00:15:34.400
really emphasizes building
intuition for why the vision

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:38.910
is the way it is and why
it's [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:38.910 --> 00:15:39.410
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:15:39.410 --> 00:15:43.070
So he emphasizes the why
of the equation.

00:15:43.070 --> 00:15:46.390
So why is it plausible that
it, for example, has--

00:15:46.390 --> 00:15:47.850
Can you give an example
of that?

00:15:47.850 --> 00:15:50.350
AUDIENCE: He talked a bit
about why [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:54.850 --> 00:15:55.380
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:15:55.380 --> 00:15:55.600
Yeah.

00:15:55.600 --> 00:15:59.560
There was an example where the
frequency was derived, so

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:01.610
emphasizes the physical
meaning and

00:16:01.610 --> 00:16:02.860
interpretations also.

00:16:11.640 --> 00:16:12.750
And interpretation.

00:16:12.750 --> 00:16:18.650
So the example he gave, which I
think is a good one, is in a

00:16:18.650 --> 00:16:24.650
pendulum, why is the period
independent of the mass?

00:16:24.650 --> 00:16:25.900
For a pendulum--

00:16:39.610 --> 00:16:39.850
OK.

00:16:39.850 --> 00:16:43.880
And the argument for that was,
oh, well, if you double the

00:16:43.880 --> 00:16:47.710
mass, you double the force, but
you double the mass, so

00:16:47.710 --> 00:16:48.945
you haven't changed
the acceleration.

00:16:48.945 --> 00:16:50.850
So everything stays the same.

00:16:50.850 --> 00:16:54.340
And he contrasted that.

00:16:54.340 --> 00:16:56.030
He didn't just do this one.

00:16:56.030 --> 00:16:59.700
He contrasted that with what
happens in a spring.

00:16:59.700 --> 00:16:59.850
OK.

00:16:59.850 --> 00:17:02.390
So how does this help
the students?

00:17:02.390 --> 00:17:03.557
What's the benefit?

00:17:03.557 --> 00:17:06.717
AUDIENCE: I think it helps them
because it makes them

00:17:06.717 --> 00:17:08.194
feel like they could potentially
derive it

00:17:08.194 --> 00:17:11.030
themselves and then afterwards
check their answer.

00:17:11.030 --> 00:17:12.089
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:17:12.089 --> 00:17:12.460
Right.

00:17:12.460 --> 00:17:14.700
He's modeling, actually,
what you would do.

00:17:14.700 --> 00:17:19.339
You, yourself, as a physicist,
and hopefully as a student,

00:17:19.339 --> 00:17:21.310
you want to be able to
check your answer by

00:17:21.310 --> 00:17:22.560
making sense of it.

00:17:31.840 --> 00:17:34.740
It promotes sense-making
is a shorthand for it.

00:17:34.740 --> 00:17:37.674
Let me just push the
other board up.

00:17:37.674 --> 00:17:39.630
AUDIENCE: Well, and it's
also [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:42.330 --> 00:17:43.360
PROFESSOR: Oh, sorry.

00:17:43.360 --> 00:17:44.818
AUDIENCE: --which is
probably the most

00:17:44.818 --> 00:17:47.020
difficult thing to teach.

00:17:47.020 --> 00:17:49.314
I thought that was the best
part of the lecture.

00:17:52.646 --> 00:17:56.454
One thing is to give a list of
facts so you learn and then

00:17:56.454 --> 00:17:57.610
you can use.

00:17:57.610 --> 00:17:58.590
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:17:58.590 --> 00:18:01.548
AUDIENCE: That seems to be the
closest to teaching how to

00:18:01.548 --> 00:18:03.273
think, which is the most
difficult thing

00:18:03.273 --> 00:18:04.510
you can ever teach.

00:18:04.510 --> 00:18:05.760
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:18:07.980 --> 00:18:09.370
It teaches how to think,
because it's a

00:18:09.370 --> 00:18:10.620
transferable skill.

00:18:16.130 --> 00:18:19.340
You may never have to analyze a
pendulum again as a student

00:18:19.340 --> 00:18:20.540
outside of the class.

00:18:20.540 --> 00:18:24.570
But whatever formula you get,
you can use that same method

00:18:24.570 --> 00:18:28.060
to say, does the formula
make sense?

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:30.750
So that's teaching a
way of thinking.

00:18:30.750 --> 00:18:32.060
It's a transferable skill.

00:18:35.259 --> 00:18:37.097
Yeah, Adrian.

00:18:37.097 --> 00:18:40.280
AUDIENCE: He's very, very
explicit about his notation.

00:18:40.280 --> 00:18:40.670
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:18:40.670 --> 00:18:41.920
Explicit about notation.

00:18:44.430 --> 00:18:45.340
Can you give an example?

00:18:45.340 --> 00:18:48.707
AUDIENCE: Well, even
when [INAUDIBLE]

