PROFESSOR: Right.

00:23:24.630 --> 00:23:27.920
One example that I remember of
that, because I was also

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:33.910
watching for that, was he wanted
to show Hooke's law and

00:23:33.910 --> 00:23:36.270
he plotted out--

00:23:36.270 --> 00:23:37.520
I'll draw an example here.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:48.720
He plotted force verses
extension for a bunch of

00:23:48.720 --> 00:23:49.340
extensions.

00:23:49.340 --> 00:23:51.050
And forces was the weight
of those springs.

00:23:51.050 --> 00:23:53.060
And he got a bunch of points
here, and he drew this.

00:23:53.060 --> 00:23:56.140
Then he pulled one of the
springs, and he stretched the

00:23:56.140 --> 00:23:58.180
hell out of it.

00:23:58.180 --> 00:24:00.780
And then he let go of it, and it
came back much longer than

00:24:00.780 --> 00:24:02.160
it started.

00:24:02.160 --> 00:24:05.750
And then he drew what happened
on the graph.

00:24:05.750 --> 00:24:09.910
So one thing he could have done,
rather than drawing it

00:24:09.910 --> 00:24:11.590
straight, is the following.

00:24:15.040 --> 00:24:18.370
You say, OK, how do we describe
what happened to that

00:24:18.370 --> 00:24:19.933
spring as I stretched it?

00:24:19.933 --> 00:24:25.180
Was it this curve, that
curve, or that curve?

00:24:25.180 --> 00:24:28.900
A, B, C. You don't have to
spend long on it, just 10

00:24:28.900 --> 00:24:32.050
seconds, or even 30 seconds.

