00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:20.340
independent of the amplitude.

00:27:20.340 --> 00:27:21.590
But why?

00:27:36.830 --> 00:27:39.440
And you can explain
that sort of

00:27:39.440 --> 00:27:42.100
intuitively just by saying--

00:27:45.680 --> 00:27:47.590
I'll give you a quick
explanation of that.

00:27:47.590 --> 00:27:50.360
So it is, actually,
an amazing fact.

00:27:50.360 --> 00:27:53.300
I'll give you a quick
explanation of the unintuitive

00:27:53.300 --> 00:27:56.140
fact that the period is
independent of the amplitude.

00:27:56.140 --> 00:27:57.390
OK?

00:28:00.940 --> 00:28:04.820
This is a scaling argument.

00:28:04.820 --> 00:28:10.830
E, G. OK.

00:28:10.830 --> 00:28:14.160
Let's estimate how long it
takes a mass to move a

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:23.140
distance, A. Well, it has some
acceleration, a, small a.

00:28:23.140 --> 00:28:25.430
This is the amplitude, and
that's the period.

00:28:25.430 --> 00:28:28.130
So the mass has some
acceleration, little a.

00:28:30.950 --> 00:28:35.675
And in some time, t, the period,
or some fraction of

00:28:35.675 --> 00:28:39.020
the period, let's say a quarter
of the period, it goes

00:28:39.020 --> 00:28:45.490
this distance, give or take
factors of 2 and whatnot.

00:28:45.490 --> 00:28:50.780
So this is roughly
the amplitude.

00:28:50.780 --> 00:28:55.210
Now we want to figure out,
what is this A here?

00:28:55.210 --> 00:29:05.180
Well, A is the force
over the mass.

00:29:07.770 --> 00:29:10.830
And the typical force, that's
coming from the spring.

00:29:10.830 --> 00:29:14.280
So it's a spring constant
times the extension.

00:29:14.280 --> 00:29:16.235
The typical extension
is the amplitude.

00:29:19.620 --> 00:29:21.100
OK?

00:29:21.100 --> 00:29:23.570
k times A is your force, divided
by m, so we'll put

00:29:23.570 --> 00:29:25.150
that in there.

00:29:25.150 --> 00:29:26.400
OK.

00:29:30.310 --> 00:29:33.260
Oh, look at that.

00:29:33.260 --> 00:29:34.510
Hmm.

00:29:36.990 --> 00:29:39.960
And in fact, there you have
t is proportional to

00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:41.800
square root of m/k.

00:29:41.800 --> 00:29:44.550
So you've got not only that
it's independent of the

00:29:44.550 --> 00:29:54.450
amplitude, but you've
got the whole story,

00:29:54.450 --> 00:29:55.650
except for the 2 pi.

00:29:55.650 --> 00:29:59.060
So intuitively, what it's saying
is that, yeah, if you

00:29:59.060 --> 00:30:02.800
move yourself farther out,
you have father to go.

00:30:02.800 --> 00:30:05.770
But you're pulled harder
by just enough to make

00:30:05.770 --> 00:30:07.770
the time the same.

00:30:07.770 --> 00:30:09.990
And so not only is
it an intuitive

00:30:09.990 --> 00:30:11.450
argument, it's very plausible.

00:30:11.450 --> 00:30:14.700
And Galileo extended it to the
pendulum, and he thought he

00:30:14.700 --> 00:30:17.870
found a proof to show that the
pendulum actually has a period

00:30:17.870 --> 00:30:20.190
independent of amplitude.

00:30:20.190 --> 00:30:23.780
In the pendulum, the amplitude
is related to the restoring

00:30:23.780 --> 00:30:27.600
force, so he thought the period
of the pendulum was

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:30.160
independent of amplitude, not
just for a regular spring.

00:30:30.160 --> 00:30:33.000
And that proof turned out to
have a slight error in it.

00:30:33.000 --> 00:30:36.760
But as Walter Lewin pointed out,
that's only true at large

00:30:36.760 --> 00:30:39.620
angles, and at small angles, you
can't tell the difference.

00:30:39.620 --> 00:30:42.570
So you can actually explain
these non-intuitive pieces in

00:30:42.570 --> 00:30:45.270
short ways that don't require
doing a full calculation.

00:30:45.270 --> 00:30:48.020
And that is important
to do, I think.

