00:32:57.600 --> 00:33:02.880
normally done in most physics
lectures on springs.

00:33:02.880 --> 00:33:07.420
The way it's normally done in
the physics class, you would

00:33:07.420 --> 00:33:11.320
do simple harmonic motion,
you'd study a whole bunch

00:33:11.320 --> 00:33:14.590
about the spring, and then maybe
a few lectures later,

00:33:14.590 --> 00:33:16.460
you might get to the pendulum.

00:33:16.460 --> 00:33:19.780
But Lewin actually did both in
the same lecture, which I

00:33:19.780 --> 00:33:22.130
thought was very interesting and
a really excellent choice.

00:33:45.410 --> 00:33:48.990
It had some negative effects,
which is that there's less

00:33:48.990 --> 00:33:52.010
time to talk about
things like this.

00:33:52.010 --> 00:33:55.040
And maybe it feels like there's
more pressure to not

00:33:55.040 --> 00:33:56.210
wait five seconds.

00:33:56.210 --> 00:33:58.080
So it has maybe subtle pressures
in the wrong

00:33:58.080 --> 00:34:02.000
direction, which maybe could
be mitigated by planning.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:05.570
But it had a really great
advantage, which is that it's

00:34:05.570 --> 00:34:06.820
this figure.

00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:14.170
So if there's some idea you want
to teach, and the idea

00:34:14.170 --> 00:34:16.239
you wanted to teach is simple
harmonic motion.

00:34:16.239 --> 00:34:21.560
He called it Simple Harmonic
Oscillation, SHM is the

00:34:21.560 --> 00:34:24.760
standard jargon in most
of the physics books.

00:34:24.760 --> 00:34:27.100
If you want to teach that idea,
just showing it in one

00:34:27.100 --> 00:34:36.050
example is not good enough for
the students, because they

00:34:36.050 --> 00:34:38.530
can't separate the example
from the idea.

00:34:38.530 --> 00:34:40.719
It's just one big morass,
and they can't draw

00:34:40.719 --> 00:34:42.000
this dividing line.

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:43.840
So you have to give them
another example.

00:34:43.840 --> 00:34:49.469
But if you give them a second
spring example, then it's

00:34:49.469 --> 00:34:50.540
still too hard.

00:34:50.540 --> 00:34:54.560
Suppose you do this and yet
another spring example.

00:34:54.560 --> 00:35:00.790
Well, the problem is it still
the overlap here is too big.

00:35:00.790 --> 00:35:03.840
So you need an example that
illustrates the core idea but

00:35:03.840 --> 00:35:05.200
is quite different.

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:07.460
And the pendulum falls into
that pretty well.

00:35:20.240 --> 00:35:23.180
It's different, in that--

00:35:23.180 --> 00:35:26.320
and the order was correct too--
he first did the spring,

00:35:26.320 --> 00:35:29.360
because the spring really is
pure simple harmonic motion.

00:35:29.360 --> 00:35:31.030
The pendulum isn't,
but you have to

00:35:31.030 --> 00:35:33.410
approximate to get it there.

00:35:33.410 --> 00:35:37.010
So it shows how you get to
simple harmonic motion,

00:35:37.010 --> 00:35:38.130
because you've seen it now.

00:35:38.130 --> 00:35:40.940
And so the piece you're getting
to is the common thing

00:35:40.940 --> 00:35:42.790
between the two examples.

00:35:42.790 --> 00:35:46.080
And furthermore, it's different
enough that you can

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:47.980
see what's common
and what's not.

00:35:47.980 --> 00:35:50.350
What's common is the structure
of the equation.

00:35:50.350 --> 00:35:51.690
The structure of the
equation is--

00:35:59.480 --> 00:36:01.020
So that's common.

00:36:01.020 --> 00:36:05.240
And so you have a really
particular example here of

00:36:05.240 --> 00:36:09.080
inducing the core idea, which
is if you just did simple

00:36:09.080 --> 00:36:12.450
harmonic motion with the example
of a spring, students

00:36:12.450 --> 00:36:14.555
may think simple harmonic
motion is this.

00:36:17.940 --> 00:36:20.160
They think whenever you
have k/m you have

00:36:20.160 --> 00:36:21.270
simple harmonic motion.

00:36:21.270 --> 00:36:23.050
Whenever you don't have
k/m, you don't have

00:36:23.050 --> 00:36:24.200
simple harmonic motion.

00:36:24.200 --> 00:36:26.130
They may think that actually
it depends on

00:36:26.130 --> 00:36:27.450
exactly what's here.

00:36:27.450 --> 00:36:29.980
But because the second example
has something completely

00:36:29.980 --> 00:36:30.590
different--

00:36:30.590 --> 00:36:38.550
The second example, the
pendulum had g/l after

00:36:38.550 --> 00:36:39.780
approximating it.

00:36:39.780 --> 00:36:43.210
You get the same structure of
the equation, but a new

00:36:43.210 --> 00:36:44.500
physical phenomena.

00:36:44.500 --> 00:36:46.720
And it shares the common
feature of

00:36:46.720 --> 00:36:47.760
simple harmonic motion.

00:36:47.760 --> 00:36:52.640
So it's a really excellent way
of bringing out this idea and

00:36:52.640 --> 00:36:55.310
borrowing most of the derivation
that he did before.

00:36:55.310 --> 00:36:59.740
For example, he didn't have to
do resolve this equation with

00:36:59.740 --> 00:37:00.980
these new parameters.

00:37:00.980 --> 00:37:04.170
Once he'd solved this equation,
all he had to do is

00:37:04.170 --> 00:37:06.220
substitute this into the
solution and get the new

00:37:06.220 --> 00:37:07.470
solution instantly.

00:37:09.990 --> 00:37:10.840
OK?

00:37:10.840 --> 00:37:12.640
Yes.

00:37:12.640 --> 00:37:14.890
AUDIENCE: He created emphasis
by using both gestures and

00:37:14.890 --> 00:37:17.570
also modulating his
pace and pitch.

00:37:17.570 --> 00:37:20.070
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:37:20.070 --> 00:37:21.880
I'll try to squeeze
it in here.

00:37:21.880 --> 00:37:24.460
So he modulated his pace
and pitch, and his

00:37:24.460 --> 00:37:27.350
gestures were very bold.

00:37:27.350 --> 00:37:28.410
He talked about the spring.

00:37:28.410 --> 00:37:29.245
He stretched the spring.

00:37:29.245 --> 00:37:32.880
He actually almost
broke the spring.

00:37:32.880 --> 00:37:36.750
Whenever he was describing
something, you could feel him

00:37:36.750 --> 00:37:38.450
feeling it in his own body.

00:37:45.760 --> 00:37:48.145
His gestures were bold, and
his pace was varied.

00:37:55.080 --> 00:37:55.340
OK.

00:37:55.340 --> 00:37:56.590
How does that help?

00:37:59.320 --> 00:38:01.215
Yeah.

00:38:01.215 --> 00:38:02.700
AUDIENCE: Conveys enthusiasm.

00:38:02.700 --> 00:38:02.940
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:38:02.940 --> 00:38:03.600
It's exciting.

00:38:03.600 --> 00:38:05.280
It conveys enthusiasm.

00:38:05.280 --> 00:38:07.750
It punctuates.

00:38:07.750 --> 00:38:09.150
There are several languages,
I think, which

00:38:09.150 --> 00:38:11.500
have no vowels and--

00:38:11.500 --> 00:38:12.690
Not no spaces.

00:38:12.690 --> 00:38:14.380
Well, German approximately
has no spaces.

00:38:14.380 --> 00:38:15.480
That's not quite true.

00:38:15.480 --> 00:38:19.250
But that don't have vowels
or punctuation.

00:38:19.250 --> 00:38:21.070
In the old days, for example,
there was no punctuation.

00:38:21.070 --> 00:38:23.450
People just ran all the words
one after another.

00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:25.780
You didn't put a period at
the end of sentences.

00:38:25.780 --> 00:38:29.320
Without punctuation, you have to
work really hard to figure

00:38:29.320 --> 00:38:32.200
out what are the units
of thought.

00:38:32.200 --> 00:38:37.010
So by varying your pace and
pitch, you convey enthusiasm.

00:38:42.750 --> 00:38:44.455
You convey enthusiasm
and structure.

00:38:48.450 --> 00:38:53.790
So the pieces that are more
important get more importance,

00:38:53.790 --> 00:38:55.490
because they're emphasized
accordingly.

00:38:59.070 --> 00:39:01.390
That's actually fundamentally
important in writing.

00:39:01.390 --> 00:39:04.770
I don't know if you know the
following recipe, but this is

00:39:04.770 --> 00:39:09.130
the first-order term in
good clear writing.

00:39:09.130 --> 00:39:12.770
Let's call it not fiction
writing but expository writing

00:39:12.770 --> 00:39:14.000
is the right word.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:17.960
The first-order term in
punctuating writing and giving

00:39:17.960 --> 00:39:19.590
structured to your
writing is this.

00:39:28.910 --> 00:39:32.850
A sentence starts with old
information that links to

00:39:32.850 --> 00:39:35.430
something before.

00:39:35.430 --> 00:39:37.280
It continues to--

00:39:47.940 --> 00:39:49.940
This is how the sentence ends.

00:39:49.940 --> 00:39:54.520
Whatever you put at the end of
the sentence, readers expect

00:39:54.520 --> 00:39:57.140
that to be the thing that
you want to emphasize.

00:39:57.140 --> 00:39:58.500
That's the new information.

00:39:58.500 --> 00:40:00.910
There's maybe a fair amount
of new information in the

00:40:00.910 --> 00:40:03.680
sentence, but this is the new
interesting information.

00:40:03.680 --> 00:40:06.500
This is what readers assume
has emphasis.

00:40:06.500 --> 00:40:09.050
And in the beginning of a
sentence, they look for things

00:40:09.050 --> 00:40:10.890
that connect to what has
already happened.

00:40:10.890 --> 00:40:13.700
It could connect to the last
emphasized thing in the last

00:40:13.700 --> 00:40:16.660
sentence, the subject of the
last sentence, the thing that

00:40:16.660 --> 00:40:18.850
was the topic, or the topic
of the paragraph.

00:40:18.850 --> 00:40:21.630
It somehow links to stuff
before, and then you're going

00:40:21.630 --> 00:40:23.530
to say something new about it.

00:40:23.530 --> 00:40:27.260
So if you don't use that order,
it gets very confusing

00:40:27.260 --> 00:40:30.150
for readers, because they expect
this to be emphasized,

00:40:30.150 --> 00:40:32.190
but you're mentally emphasizing
something else,

00:40:32.190 --> 00:40:34.630
and then they have to redo their
expectations each time.

00:40:34.630 --> 00:40:37.790
So punctuation, the period
actually is a way of saying,

00:40:37.790 --> 00:40:39.830
here came the most important
information.

00:40:39.830 --> 00:40:42.400
And if you follow that
structure, you'll tap into

00:40:42.400 --> 00:40:45.450
much better how your
readers understand.

00:40:45.450 --> 00:40:49.290
If you want to know more about
that, I'll put some references

00:40:49.290 --> 00:40:50.540
on the website.

00:40:57.600 --> 00:41:01.475
This was partly developed by
Joseph Williams, a linguistic

00:41:01.475 --> 00:41:04.790
at the University of Chicago
and George Gopen, who's an

00:41:04.790 --> 00:41:08.400
English professor and law
professor at Duke.

00:41:08.400 --> 00:41:11.170
And he's written a really
interesting article called,

00:41:11.170 --> 00:41:12.460
him and Judith Swan--
it's called "The

00:41:12.460 --> 00:41:13.820
Science of Science Writing"--

00:41:13.820 --> 00:41:16.930
where he gives a whole bunch of
examples of restructuring

00:41:16.930 --> 00:41:19.680
prose along these lines and how
much clearer it becomes.

00:41:19.680 --> 00:41:25.560
And he's written two books,
actually, one on teaching this

00:41:25.560 --> 00:41:28.990
approach to writing and one
on doing it yourself.

00:41:28.990 --> 00:41:31.760
It's a textbook for
such a class.

00:41:31.760 --> 00:41:33.290
One's called The Sense
of Structure.

00:41:33.290 --> 00:41:36.580
I forget whether that's the
teaching book or the textbook.

00:41:36.580 --> 00:41:39.670
But I'll put both titles on
the website So I highly

00:41:39.670 --> 00:41:40.690
recommend that.

00:41:40.690 --> 00:41:44.360
And what you'll see from this
is the huge importance of

00:41:44.360 --> 00:41:45.610
punctuation.

00:41:48.080 --> 00:41:50.070
And here, it's the same thing.

00:41:50.070 --> 00:41:53.340
By varying the pitch, by giving
periods, semicolons,

00:41:53.340 --> 00:41:57.080
and commas in the lecture, even
though you can't say, OK,

00:41:57.080 --> 00:41:58.390
here's the period.

00:41:58.390 --> 00:42:01.600
You don't say that, but you do
it by varying your pitch and

00:42:01.600 --> 00:42:03.040
your volume and your tone.

00:42:03.040 --> 00:42:04.110
You give structure.

00:42:04.110 --> 00:42:07.450
And fundamentally important,
you also convey enthusiasm.

00:42:07.450 --> 00:42:07.760
Yes.

00:42:07.760 --> 00:42:10.410
AUDIENCE: On the other hand,
I think in that lecture he

00:42:10.410 --> 00:42:12.020
offered [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:12.020 --> 00:42:12.200
[LOUDLY]

00:42:12.200 --> 00:42:14.980
he always speaks like this,
[NORMAL VOLUME]

00:42:14.980 --> 00:42:16.570
which intimidated
students a bit.

00:42:16.570 --> 00:42:17.750
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:42:17.750 --> 00:42:18.470
Yeah.

00:42:18.470 --> 00:42:20.380
He maybe does it too much.

00:42:20.380 --> 00:42:23.240
In fact, he doesn't
vary enough.

00:42:23.240 --> 00:42:27.720
It's sort of like the
radio in Spinal Tap.

00:42:27.720 --> 00:42:31.410
It goes to 11, and
it starts at 10.

00:42:31.410 --> 00:42:32.910
Because it's always loud.

00:42:32.910 --> 00:42:35.040
The amplifier's always loud.

00:42:35.040 --> 00:42:36.620
Yeah, I think he could
actually have

00:42:36.620 --> 00:42:38.690
more dynamic range.

00:42:38.690 --> 00:42:40.250
So let's see.

00:42:40.250 --> 00:42:41.500
More--

00:42:48.400 --> 00:42:49.350
In his defense--

00:42:49.350 --> 00:42:50.630
Oh, yes.

00:42:50.630 --> 00:42:51.086
Go ahead.

00:42:51.086 --> 00:42:52.130
AUDIENCE: Finish your thought.

00:42:52.130 --> 00:42:53.000
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:57.680
In his defense, you could say,
well, when do you want to be

00:42:57.680 --> 00:42:58.690
really quiet?

00:42:58.690 --> 00:42:59.520
Well, that's when you're doing

00:42:59.520 --> 00:43:01.280
something that's less important.

00:43:01.280 --> 00:43:03.730
And he's actually such a good
lecturer that he planned the

00:43:03.730 --> 00:43:04.860
lecture, I would say,
quite well.

00:43:04.860 --> 00:43:07.890
He took out all the stuff that
normally you would find in a

00:43:07.890 --> 00:43:09.980
lecture on this that's
kind of dull.

00:43:09.980 --> 00:43:13.090
For example, one thing that
people do that's really kind

00:43:13.090 --> 00:43:17.710
of dull is they may derive the
sinusoid as a solution.

00:43:17.710 --> 00:43:18.960
And how did he derive
the sinusoid?

00:43:23.400 --> 00:43:26.180
Spray paint.

00:43:26.180 --> 00:43:28.200
They did an experiment.

00:43:28.200 --> 00:43:29.170
He made it visible.

00:43:29.170 --> 00:43:33.170
He had a spring oscillating up
and down with spray paint, so

00:43:33.170 --> 00:43:35.340
it was spraying on a
big piece of paper.

00:43:35.340 --> 00:43:38.300
And then he pulled the piece
of paper that way.

00:43:38.300 --> 00:43:41.450
So as the spring oscillated up
and down and sprayed on the

00:43:41.450 --> 00:43:44.700
sheet of paper, it made a track,
which you could see

00:43:44.700 --> 00:43:45.500
developing.

00:43:45.500 --> 00:43:46.850
And then he just showed
the class.

00:43:46.850 --> 00:43:47.860
He said, what does
this look like?

00:43:47.860 --> 00:43:49.310
And they said, oh, it looks
like a sinusoid.

00:43:49.310 --> 00:43:50.450
There you go.

00:43:50.450 --> 00:43:55.890
Now you skipped a whole bunch of
painful math, otherwise, to

00:43:55.890 --> 00:43:57.030
make the guess.

00:43:57.030 --> 00:44:01.520
And so either you guess it, or
you do a bunch of derivation.

00:44:01.520 --> 00:44:03.670
He avoided both of those
problems by actually just

00:44:03.670 --> 00:44:05.690
having the students see
for themselves.

00:44:05.690 --> 00:44:07.452
In fact, he used the word see.

00:44:07.452 --> 00:44:09.390
I want to make you
see what it is.

00:44:09.390 --> 00:44:10.600
So he got that.

00:44:10.600 --> 00:44:14.560
He's taken out a lot of stuff
where you would normally just

00:44:14.560 --> 00:44:15.900
try to pretend you
weren't doing and

00:44:15.900 --> 00:44:17.380
speak really quietly.

00:44:17.380 --> 00:44:19.390
So that's maybe one explanation
for why his

00:44:19.390 --> 00:44:22.510
dynamic range wasn't as
big as it should be.

00:44:22.510 --> 00:44:26.960
But yeah, I think, generally,
the point is right that he's

00:44:26.960 --> 00:44:31.410
so forceful and loud that it
would be better if he just had

00:44:31.410 --> 00:44:32.720
a twice as much range.

00:44:32.720 --> 00:44:33.980
AUDIENCE: Just an
extra comment.

00:44:33.980 --> 00:44:34.467
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:44:34.467 --> 00:44:36.415
AUDIENCE: And this maybe be
necessary in the old days when

00:44:36.415 --> 00:44:37.876
you don't have microphones
in lectures.

00:44:37.876 --> 00:44:40.554
But when you have microphones,
you can speak colloquially but

00:44:40.554 --> 00:44:43.240
still very clear to
the students.

00:44:43.240 --> 00:44:43.500
PROFESSOR: That's true.

00:44:43.500 --> 00:44:44.275
You have amplification.

00:44:44.275 --> 00:44:44.580
Yeah.

00:44:44.580 --> 00:44:49.410
And he did have a microphone,
because he was being taped.

00:44:49.410 --> 00:44:50.300
But you're right.

00:44:50.300 --> 00:44:53.010
The habits of thought in
presentation come from when we

00:44:53.010 --> 00:44:54.450
didn't have microphones.

00:44:54.450 --> 00:44:56.282
Yes.

00:44:56.282 --> 00:44:58.999
AUDIENCE: The one thing I would
change is at the very

00:44:58.999 --> 00:45:00.728
beginning he was talking
about the test results.

00:45:00.728 --> 00:45:01.222
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:45:01.222 --> 00:45:04.680
AUDIENCE: And he said the test
results were better, on

00:45:04.680 --> 00:45:06.656
average, than in
previous years.

00:45:06.656 --> 00:45:10.361
And he said, oh, you're either
a smart class or the

00:45:10.361 --> 00:45:13.078
test was too easy.

00:45:13.078 --> 00:45:16.900
Just generally, calling the
students smart seems pretty

00:45:16.900 --> 00:45:19.214
alienating for the students
who did poorly.

00:45:19.214 --> 00:45:21.410
And then even the kids who did
well, there's pretty good

00:45:21.410 --> 00:45:23.290
evidence that saying "you're
smart" rather than "you're

00:45:23.290 --> 00:45:27.530
working hard", the latter's
much more effective.

00:45:27.530 --> 00:45:27.670
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:45:27.670 --> 00:45:29.690
That's a really good point.

00:45:29.690 --> 00:45:33.560
Yeah, the test results
discussion at the beginning.

00:45:33.560 --> 00:45:39.470
I always knew this lecture was a
classic one, and this is the

00:45:39.470 --> 00:45:41.780
first time I watched it straight
through, rather than

00:45:41.780 --> 00:45:43.930
just watching the sort of
demonstration parts and the

00:45:43.930 --> 00:45:45.500
famous parts.

00:45:45.500 --> 00:45:48.950
And so it started off with this
discussion about test

00:45:48.950 --> 00:45:56.730
results where he says all kinds
of interesting things.

00:45:56.730 --> 00:45:59.280
"You did very well on your first
exam." That's word one

00:45:59.280 --> 00:46:00.770
in the lecture.

00:46:00.770 --> 00:46:05.830
"I was hoping for an average
of about 75." So hoping,

00:46:05.830 --> 00:46:08.420
that's not a word I
would have used.

00:46:08.420 --> 00:46:10.070
I would hope for an
average of 100.

00:46:10.070 --> 00:46:10.990
That's my hope.

00:46:10.990 --> 00:46:14.240
Maybe not what I expect,
but my hope is 100.

00:46:14.240 --> 00:46:17.590
So by saying hope, he's saying,
actually, it would be

00:46:17.590 --> 00:46:20.880
good if people got a lot of
stuff wrong, like I'm hoping

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:22.890
that people get 25% wrong.

00:46:22.890 --> 00:46:25.170
That could be interpreted
as hoping that the

00:46:25.170 --> 00:46:26.900
students don't do great.

00:46:26.900 --> 00:46:29.020
But then, on the other hand,
the class average was 89.

00:46:29.020 --> 00:46:29.230
OK.

00:46:29.230 --> 00:46:30.640
So that's good news.

00:46:30.640 --> 00:46:34.300
Now, as you say, he says,
"either you are very smart,

00:46:34.300 --> 00:46:37.655
this is an exceptional class, or
the exam was too easy." And

00:46:37.655 --> 00:46:40.140
he eventually concludes, no,
the exam was taken by the

00:46:40.140 --> 00:46:42.110
instructor, so you guys
are smart class.

00:46:42.110 --> 00:46:47.510
But even that he takes away by
saying, "but time will tell

00:46:47.510 --> 00:46:49.590
whether you are indeed
exceptionally smart or whether

00:46:49.590 --> 00:46:51.300
the exam was too easy."

00:46:51.300 --> 00:46:53.970
So even the good news
is tempered and

00:46:53.970 --> 00:46:55.190
taken partly back.

00:46:55.190 --> 00:46:57.440
And then even the good news
itself, as you point out

00:46:57.440 --> 00:47:00.430
correctly, is not necessarily
good for helping

00:47:00.430 --> 00:47:01.890
the students learn.

00:47:01.890 --> 00:47:04.530
So there's very interesting
studies--

00:47:04.530 --> 00:47:05.700
I wish I could remember
the name.

00:47:05.700 --> 00:47:08.900
She's a psychology professor
at Stanford, and she's done

00:47:08.900 --> 00:47:13.190
studies with kids.

00:47:13.190 --> 00:47:20.000
What you do is you have the kids
do a problem, and then

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:24.510
you tell them either that they
worked hard at it or that they

00:47:24.510 --> 00:47:25.850
were very smart.

00:47:25.850 --> 00:47:28.650
That's why they solved it.

00:47:28.650 --> 00:47:32.480
You tell Group A that,
oh, yeah, you worked

00:47:32.480 --> 00:47:33.640
really hard at it.

00:47:33.640 --> 00:47:34.430
That's why you solved it.

00:47:34.430 --> 00:47:36.315
Group B, you say, oh,
yeah, you solved it.

00:47:36.315 --> 00:47:37.650
You must be really smart.

00:47:37.650 --> 00:47:39.930
And then you see what kind of
problems they try later.

00:47:44.930 --> 00:47:47.640
Let's do Group B first, who are
told you did it because

00:47:47.640 --> 00:47:49.710
you were smart.

00:47:49.710 --> 00:47:50.490
Later--

00:47:50.490 --> 00:47:53.220
this is making an extreme of
it, but this is the trend--

00:47:53.220 --> 00:47:55.850
they don't want to solve
hard problems.

00:47:55.850 --> 00:47:58.220
Because the only thing you can
get out of solving a hard

00:47:58.220 --> 00:48:00.280
problem is you don't solve it,
which then proves that you're

00:48:00.280 --> 00:48:02.490
actually not as smart
as people though.

00:48:02.490 --> 00:48:04.560
So they want to solve
easy problems.

00:48:04.560 --> 00:48:07.100
The group that was told, oh,
yeah, you did that because you

00:48:07.100 --> 00:48:10.420
worked really hard, they enjoy
solving the problems.

00:48:10.420 --> 00:48:13.010
And they want to solve hard
problems that they can't

00:48:13.010 --> 00:48:14.720
necessarily solve, because
they can work on them.

00:48:14.720 --> 00:48:17.720
And some of them even say things
like, oh, I love it

00:48:17.720 --> 00:48:21.060
when a problem's hard, which
is a completely different

00:48:21.060 --> 00:48:23.130
attitude than the attitude of
the people who are like, oh, I

00:48:23.130 --> 00:48:23.980
don't want to try anything.

00:48:23.980 --> 00:48:26.440
Because I might fail, and
then the truth about

00:48:26.440 --> 00:48:28.560
me will come out.

00:48:28.560 --> 00:48:31.240
By making comments about
people's intrinsic

00:48:31.240 --> 00:48:33.390
characteristics--

00:48:33.390 --> 00:48:35.880
I made distinction earlier
between intrinsic motivation

00:48:35.880 --> 00:48:38.800
and extrinsic motivation and
how you really want to use

00:48:38.800 --> 00:48:40.580
intrinsic motivation.

00:48:40.580 --> 00:48:44.320
But there's the flip one, which
is you don't want to

00:48:44.320 --> 00:48:47.470
make intrinsic comments about
people, because that's very

00:48:47.470 --> 00:48:50.140
hard to change and very fixed.

00:48:50.140 --> 00:48:52.330
And that's what people are
doing way too much of.

00:48:52.330 --> 00:48:54.670
So whenever people can't solve
things, it's because you

00:48:54.670 --> 00:48:57.185
didn't work hard enough, the
conditions weren't right, you

00:48:57.185 --> 00:48:59.300
can call it making excuses,
but it isn't.

00:48:59.300 --> 00:49:01.630
It's an optimistic way of
looking at the world.

00:49:01.630 --> 00:49:04.910
And it's that optimism that
people learn when they have

00:49:04.910 --> 00:49:07.420
control over the things that
lead to problem-solving

00:49:07.420 --> 00:49:09.360
successfully or not.

00:49:09.360 --> 00:49:12.660
Yeah, I thought the opening was
actually very bad in terms

00:49:12.660 --> 00:49:17.050
of that and actually set
a kind of competitive,

00:49:17.050 --> 00:49:22.220
hierarchical tone, which I would
have definitely avoided.

00:49:22.220 --> 00:49:23.330
Other comments?

00:49:23.330 --> 00:49:26.780
Other things you noticed?

00:49:26.780 --> 00:49:27.262
Yeah.

00:49:27.262 --> 00:49:29.190
AUDIENCE: He kind of oozed with

00:49:29.190 --> 00:49:31.118
passion about the subject.

00:49:31.118 --> 00:49:34.492
Usually, [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:34.492 --> 00:49:37.880
5,000, he still seemed amazed
that they worked.

00:49:37.880 --> 00:49:39.580
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:49:39.580 --> 00:49:40.710
Right.

00:49:40.710 --> 00:49:44.280
Let me erase this guy.

00:49:44.280 --> 00:49:45.820
Right.

00:49:45.820 --> 00:49:47.150
He's shedding passion.

00:49:47.150 --> 00:49:48.400
He's oozing passion.

00:49:53.800 --> 00:49:56.880
I'm sure he's done the demo
many, many times for every

00:49:56.880 --> 00:49:59.320
semester, no doubt.

00:49:59.320 --> 00:50:01.880
Yet he was still so excited.

00:50:01.880 --> 00:50:04.040
For example, the ending,
what did he say?

00:50:08.870 --> 00:50:11.480
They did 10 oscillations
with Walter Lewin as

00:50:11.480 --> 00:50:13.330
the pendulum bob.

00:50:13.330 --> 00:50:15.200
And then they counted
up to 10.

00:50:15.200 --> 00:50:19.870
So then he got to 10t with
Walter Lewin, 45.6, plus or

00:50:19.870 --> 00:50:21.090
minus 0.1 seconds.

00:50:21.090 --> 00:50:24.940
And the prediction was 45.7,
plus or minus 0.1, so it was

00:50:24.940 --> 00:50:25.680
right on the nose.

00:50:25.680 --> 00:50:28.010
He said, "Physics works,
I'm telling you.

00:50:28.010 --> 00:50:32.820
See you Monday." So he
ends with enthusiasm.

00:50:32.820 --> 00:50:36.170
He is enthusiasm throughout,
all the way through.

00:50:36.170 --> 00:50:38.020
Yeah, it is contagious.

00:50:38.020 --> 00:50:39.880
People did applaud, and I'm sure
it wasn't just because it

00:50:39.880 --> 00:50:40.680
was being taped.

00:50:40.680 --> 00:50:46.210
They really were very pleased
and amazed at the close

00:50:46.210 --> 00:50:49.360
agreement, even when he changed
the pendulum bob from

00:50:49.360 --> 00:50:52.260
just the regular pendulum bob
of a few kilograms to Walter

00:50:52.260 --> 00:50:54.320
Lewin of 70 kilograms or--

00:50:54.320 --> 00:50:56.190
he's probably more--

00:50:56.190 --> 00:50:58.720
probably 80 kilograms.

00:50:58.720 --> 00:51:03.530
And throughout as well, doing
the demonstrations, he was

00:51:03.530 --> 00:51:04.700
also very enthusiastic.

00:51:04.700 --> 00:51:07.820
And even sometimes he got lucky,
and he even said so.

00:51:07.820 --> 00:51:11.600
But he said, fantastic agreement
between theory and

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:12.720
experiment.

00:51:12.720 --> 00:51:16.240
Yeah, so the enthusiasm,
it transfers.

00:51:16.240 --> 00:51:21.760
And in fact, our system, our
brain is actually much better

00:51:21.760 --> 00:51:24.930
at picking up this kind of stuff
than it is at picking up

00:51:24.930 --> 00:51:27.560
the Navier-Stokes equation
and things like that.

00:51:31.540 --> 00:51:34.062
Let's call it an emotional
highway.

00:51:34.062 --> 00:51:35.440
It goes in the emotional
highway.

00:51:40.860 --> 00:51:43.390
So I mentioned the experiment
that you can do to test this.

00:51:43.390 --> 00:51:46.600
The experiment you do is you
just go somewhere and you just

00:51:46.600 --> 00:51:47.850
smile at people.

00:51:50.230 --> 00:51:55.070
And now 30%, 40%, 50% of the
class is smiling back already.

00:51:55.070 --> 00:51:56.270
You can't help it.

00:51:56.270 --> 00:51:57.740
Even though you know
and I'm telling you

00:51:57.740 --> 00:51:58.450
I'm just doing this--

00:51:58.450 --> 00:52:00.550
There's nothing actually funny
that just happened right now.

00:52:00.550 --> 00:52:02.930
I'm just smiling, just because
I'm a nice guy and I'm

00:52:02.930 --> 00:52:05.610
smiling, and I just wanted you
to see if the experiment

00:52:05.610 --> 00:52:07.830
works-- you can't help it.

00:52:07.830 --> 00:52:11.290
So that tells you how powerful
that emotional highway is.

00:52:11.290 --> 00:52:12.740
It's not just for smiling.

00:52:12.740 --> 00:52:16.600
It's the oozing passion.

00:52:16.600 --> 00:52:19.990
Neurobiologically, that
mechanism is starting to be

00:52:19.990 --> 00:52:22.700
understood.

00:52:22.700 --> 00:52:24.000
I'll write the mechanism down.

00:52:32.320 --> 00:52:35.240
We have what are called
mirror neurons.

00:52:35.240 --> 00:52:41.240
What mirror neurons do is they
recreate the state of mind of

00:52:41.240 --> 00:52:44.140
other people in us.

00:52:44.140 --> 00:52:45.970
So that's why they're called
mirror neurons.

00:52:45.970 --> 00:52:47.200
And they're innate.

00:52:47.200 --> 00:52:48.810
It seems that monkeys
have them.

00:52:48.810 --> 00:52:49.520
We have them.

00:52:49.520 --> 00:52:50.840
There's nothing you
can do about them.

00:52:50.840 --> 00:52:53.850
And they are actually probably
the mechanism by which we

00:52:53.850 --> 00:52:55.850
become social creatures
and which

00:52:55.850 --> 00:52:57.760
makes us social creatures.

00:52:57.760 --> 00:53:00.360
So if people around us are
unhappy, we feel unhappy.

00:53:00.360 --> 00:53:03.200
If people around us are
happy, we feel happy.

00:53:03.200 --> 00:53:06.060
And these mirror neurons, their
firing tendencies are

00:53:06.060 --> 00:53:09.480
partly set in young childhood.

00:53:09.480 --> 00:53:12.430
So if the people around you are
happy in childhood, you'll

00:53:12.430 --> 00:53:14.240
have a much easier time just

00:53:14.240 --> 00:53:15.670
automatically being happy later.

00:53:15.670 --> 00:53:17.960
And if the people around you
in childhood are really

00:53:17.960 --> 00:53:20.660
unhappy and your childhood's
unhappy, you have to work much

00:53:20.660 --> 00:53:22.610
harder later to overcome that.

00:53:22.610 --> 00:53:26.080
So that's the importance
of childhood and child

00:53:26.080 --> 00:53:26.870
upbringing.

00:53:26.870 --> 00:53:30.620
But now these are there, and
your students all have them,

00:53:30.620 --> 00:53:31.470
being people.

00:53:31.470 --> 00:53:36.170
So how you act and how you
perform is going to affect

00:53:36.170 --> 00:53:40.920
them much more strongly than
any equation you say.

00:53:40.920 --> 00:53:43.820
It's fundamentally
important, again.

00:53:43.820 --> 00:53:44.160
OK.

00:53:44.160 --> 00:53:45.410
Any other points?

00:53:48.440 --> 00:53:48.920
Yes.

00:53:48.920 --> 00:53:49.400
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:53:49.400 --> 00:53:53.482
I was thinking about the
use of the spray--

00:53:53.482 --> 00:53:54.650
PROFESSOR: The spray paint can?

00:53:54.650 --> 00:53:54.920
Yeah.

00:53:54.920 --> 00:53:56.327
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:53:56.327 --> 00:53:58.203
And it wasn't until now
that I actually

00:53:58.203 --> 00:53:59.610
understood why he did that.

00:53:59.610 --> 00:54:04.746
Because when I saw it, I was
sort of thinking, why is he

00:54:04.746 --> 00:54:05.698
doing that?

00:54:05.698 --> 00:54:08.078
Or if he pulled the
lever faster, it's

00:54:08.078 --> 00:54:11.410
going to look the same.

00:54:11.410 --> 00:54:12.990
I didn't get it at all.

00:54:12.990 --> 00:54:16.802
And now I see it was to guess
the solution [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:16.802 --> 00:54:23.185
And then I'm thinking, when
I was taught the harmonic

00:54:23.185 --> 00:54:26.622
oscillator for the first time,
that's an opportunity the

00:54:26.622 --> 00:54:29.904
professor used to actually teach
how to solve, OK, this

00:54:29.904 --> 00:54:32.162
is the differential equation,
and this is the

00:54:32.162 --> 00:54:32.808
solution for it.

00:54:32.808 --> 00:54:34.750
And now you know for the
rest of your life.

00:54:34.750 --> 00:54:38.810
Because solving a differential
equation by [INAUDIBLE],

00:54:38.810 --> 00:54:41.640
you're not always going to have
an experiment to solve--

00:54:41.640 --> 00:54:42.280
PROFESSOR: To show it.

00:54:42.280 --> 00:54:44.730
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:54:44.730 --> 00:54:45.730
It's kind of cool.

00:54:45.730 --> 00:54:48.730
But I'm not quite sure
what's the purpose.

00:54:48.730 --> 00:54:49.070
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:54:49.070 --> 00:54:51.900
So what's the purpose?

00:54:51.900 --> 00:54:57.510
It could go here or here,
the spray paint example.

00:54:57.510 --> 00:55:02.250
The normal way it's done is that
you either just guess it

00:55:02.250 --> 00:55:05.640
outright, you say, well, we've
seen that equation before--

00:55:05.640 --> 00:55:08.220
we being the royal we-- the
instructor's seen the equation

00:55:08.220 --> 00:55:11.180
before and says, use
the sinusoid.

00:55:11.180 --> 00:55:12.790
The students have never seen
it before and just have to

00:55:12.790 --> 00:55:14.350
take it on faith.

00:55:14.350 --> 00:55:16.710
Then you put in the sinusoid,
and then you show that it

00:55:16.710 --> 00:55:18.640
solves the equation.

00:55:18.640 --> 00:55:22.370
The other way you do it is you
separate the equation.

00:55:22.370 --> 00:55:24.270
There's many techniques for
solving that equation.

00:55:24.270 --> 00:55:29.330
One is you write it in terms
of operators and factor the

00:55:29.330 --> 00:55:33.180
operators, but the freshman
aren't really ready for that.

00:55:33.180 --> 00:55:34.200
So you can't really do that.

00:55:34.200 --> 00:55:37.440
You're basically reduced to
guessing, at least in the

00:55:37.440 --> 00:55:39.060
American curriculum.

00:55:39.060 --> 00:55:41.960
Now what he's done is he's done
an improvement on that.

00:55:41.960 --> 00:55:45.950
Instead of saying just by bold
assertion, just outright

00:55:45.950 --> 00:55:49.470
authority saying, please guess
this, he's saying, look, this

00:55:49.470 --> 00:55:50.210
is what it did.

00:55:50.210 --> 00:55:51.690
What do you think it is?

00:55:51.690 --> 00:55:53.450
And then the students say,
oh, it's a sinusoid.

00:55:53.450 --> 00:55:54.740
He says, OK, good.

00:55:54.740 --> 00:55:56.810
That justifies the guess,
basically, that I was going to

00:55:56.810 --> 00:55:57.950
make anyway.

00:55:57.950 --> 00:56:00.980
So it improves on the standard
method of guessing and just

00:56:00.980 --> 00:56:01.680
plugging in.

00:56:01.680 --> 00:56:02.610
But you're right.

00:56:02.610 --> 00:56:04.130
Not always can you do that.

00:56:04.130 --> 00:56:07.080
So maybe the thing I would have
done is, if I were him, I

00:56:07.080 --> 00:56:10.630
would have said, ah, this is
going to avoid us just either

00:56:10.630 --> 00:56:14.200
guessing the solution or doing a
whole big, long calculation.

00:56:14.200 --> 00:56:20.390
And he does say that elsewhere
when he talks about the zoo,

00:56:20.390 --> 00:56:22.620
when he wrote down the
differential equations for the

00:56:22.620 --> 00:56:24.850
x motion and the y motion.

00:56:24.850 --> 00:56:27.990
He said, oh, that has a coupled
nonlinear equation.

00:56:27.990 --> 00:56:28.395
It's hopeless.

00:56:28.395 --> 00:56:32.000
It looks like a zoo,
and it is a zoo.

00:56:32.000 --> 00:56:33.930
So then he approximated it.

00:56:33.930 --> 00:56:36.310
He was quite good at saying,
look, there's some things you

00:56:36.310 --> 00:56:37.660
just don't want to do.

00:56:37.660 --> 00:56:38.920
And this would have
been, I think,

00:56:38.920 --> 00:56:40.130
another spot to do that.

00:56:40.130 --> 00:56:42.600
He could have explained why
he was going to do the

00:56:42.600 --> 00:56:43.850
experiment.

00:56:54.640 --> 00:56:55.080
OK.

00:56:55.080 --> 00:57:00.820
Just one other point, I think,
that wasn't mentioned so far.

00:57:00.820 --> 00:57:02.880
Oh, yeah.

00:57:02.880 --> 00:57:07.850
Yeah, he never erases
what he's using.

00:57:07.850 --> 00:57:10.560
We'll talk about that more the
next time when we talk about

00:57:10.560 --> 00:57:12.190
using chalk and slides.

00:57:12.190 --> 00:57:15.360
If you notice, he never erased
anything he needed.

00:57:15.360 --> 00:57:17.930
Now you could just
call that chance.

00:57:17.930 --> 00:57:19.990
So an example of when
he had stuff that

00:57:19.990 --> 00:57:21.890
he was using before.

00:57:21.890 --> 00:57:35.420
He had the differential
equation, and then that was

00:57:35.420 --> 00:57:36.850
way up on some board.

00:57:36.850 --> 00:57:39.600
And then later, after doing the
experiment with the spray

00:57:39.600 --> 00:57:41.912
paint, he came to x equals--

00:57:48.300 --> 00:57:52.850
So now he had to calculate x and
x dot, the derivative, and

00:57:52.850 --> 00:57:54.840
x double dot and
then put it in.

00:57:54.840 --> 00:57:57.380
Well, as he was doing that,
fortunately this equation was

00:57:57.380 --> 00:57:58.660
still there the whole time.

00:57:58.660 --> 00:57:59.940
It was just high up.

00:57:59.940 --> 00:58:02.560
So he never erased anything
he needed later.

00:58:02.560 --> 00:58:03.960
And I was watching
pretty carefully

00:58:03.960 --> 00:58:05.040
through the whole lecture.

00:58:05.040 --> 00:58:07.490
I think there was no time
when that had happened.

00:58:07.490 --> 00:58:10.100
And you could call
that chance.

00:58:10.100 --> 00:58:12.130
Maybe if it happened once
it would just be chance.

00:58:12.130 --> 00:58:14.270
But it's actually preparation.

00:58:14.270 --> 00:58:16.230
So that's part of lecture
preparation.

00:58:16.230 --> 00:58:17.460
What am I going to need?

00:58:17.460 --> 00:58:22.350
And how do I make sure that
it's still visible?

00:58:22.350 --> 00:58:23.370
Or you can write it again.

00:58:23.370 --> 00:58:24.330
That's also fine.

00:58:24.330 --> 00:58:26.445
But how do I make it so that
students don't have to

00:58:26.445 --> 00:58:28.030
remember it, flip back
in their notes?

00:58:28.030 --> 00:58:30.220
Because to them, this
is a new equation.

00:58:30.220 --> 00:58:33.580
It's not just the equivalent
of one pawn, one chunk.

00:58:33.580 --> 00:58:35.660
It's six or seven chunks.

00:58:35.660 --> 00:58:37.430
So you don't want to fill up
their short-term memory trying

00:58:37.430 --> 00:58:38.260
to remember that.

00:58:38.260 --> 00:58:39.890
You want it visible somewhere.

00:58:39.890 --> 00:58:41.625
And that was also planning.

00:58:45.850 --> 00:58:46.105
Yes.

00:58:46.105 --> 00:58:49.120
AUDIENCE: He calls
tension a force.

00:58:49.120 --> 00:58:50.710
PROFESSOR: Yeah, he did
call tension a force.

00:58:50.710 --> 00:58:53.680
I was most upset about that.

00:58:53.680 --> 00:59:03.540
That is the standard way it's
done, and all the physics

00:59:03.540 --> 00:59:04.510
courses I took as
an undergraduate

00:59:04.510 --> 00:59:05.560
did the same thing.

00:59:05.560 --> 00:59:08.350
And I'm sure that's how I
got confused about it.

00:59:08.350 --> 00:59:09.820
I'm sure most people
are confused about

00:59:09.820 --> 00:59:10.930
it because of that.

00:59:10.930 --> 00:59:13.920
And until they do a few thought
experiments or have to

00:59:13.920 --> 00:59:16.360
teach it and really sort through
it, they won't figure

00:59:16.360 --> 00:59:17.790
out that it's actually
not a force.

00:59:17.790 --> 00:59:20.820
Now I'm sure Walter Lewin
doesn't internally think of it

00:59:20.820 --> 00:59:21.190
as a force.

00:59:21.190 --> 00:59:22.740
He knows it behaves
differently.

00:59:22.740 --> 00:59:27.070
But it's so easy to use this
shorthand, and then the

00:59:27.070 --> 00:59:29.740
students, they don't have any
other structure for it.

00:59:29.740 --> 00:59:31.250
They'll just think it does
act like a force.

00:59:31.250 --> 00:59:34.090
It add vectors, but
it doesn't.

00:59:34.090 --> 00:59:34.400
Yeah.

00:59:34.400 --> 00:59:37.000
So that was, I thought,
a dubious point.

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:40.170
But it's standard,
unfortunately.

00:59:40.170 --> 00:59:41.985
It's a good lesson that just
because something's standard

00:59:41.985 --> 00:59:45.735
doesn't mean it's a
good thing to do.

00:59:45.735 --> 00:59:46.685
Yep.

00:59:46.685 --> 00:59:49.070
AUDIENCE: He used the big
chalk and colors.

00:59:49.070 --> 00:59:50.660
PROFESSOR: Yeah, big yeah.

00:59:50.660 --> 00:59:53.180
Right.

00:59:53.180 --> 00:59:55.350
Actually, if you need to order
this chalk, it's called

00:59:55.350 --> 00:59:56.600
railroad crayon.

01:00:07.690 --> 01:00:10.150
You want to be careful to get
railroad crayon, because there

01:00:10.150 --> 01:00:14.200
is actually big chalk you can
buy from, I don't know,

01:00:14.200 --> 01:00:16.040
variety stores.

01:00:16.040 --> 01:00:19.560
And that's for, for example,
writing messages on sidewalks.

01:00:19.560 --> 01:00:22.770
And the problem with that is
that has wax in it so that it

01:00:22.770 --> 01:00:25.160
stays against the rain.

01:00:25.160 --> 01:00:28.000
But that's not so good
for the blackboard.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:29.390
It's much harder to get off.

01:00:29.390 --> 01:00:32.910
Railroad crayon is designed
to be removed easily.

01:00:32.910 --> 01:00:35.450
If you order railroad crayon,
unfortunately it seems to come

01:00:35.450 --> 01:00:39.150
in boxes of 144.

01:00:39.150 --> 01:00:41.140
Maybe you can get a box of 72.

01:00:41.140 --> 01:00:43.220
So share it around.

01:00:43.220 --> 01:00:45.680
If you find a source with
smaller amounts, let me know.

01:00:45.680 --> 01:00:49.660
But the ones we found were 144,
a gross, one dozen dozen.

01:00:49.660 --> 01:00:52.450
But yeah, he used railroad
crayon, so it was very easy to

01:00:52.450 --> 01:00:53.790
see what he was doing.

01:00:53.790 --> 01:00:55.150
And he used colors.

01:00:55.150 --> 01:00:57.360
For example, forces
were always read.

01:00:57.360 --> 01:01:00.590
And he used a consistent naming
convention for that, so

01:01:00.590 --> 01:01:02.530
he wasn't throwing noise
onto the system.

01:01:02.530 --> 01:01:02.720
Yeah.

01:01:02.720 --> 01:01:04.970
AUDIENCE: This was mentioned
before, but I think one

01:01:04.970 --> 01:01:06.827
important thing he did
is that he created

01:01:06.827 --> 01:01:09.234
suspense by taking a risk.

01:01:09.234 --> 01:01:11.210
Because he repeated the full
experiment in class.

01:01:11.210 --> 01:01:12.692
Because [INAUDIBLE].

01:01:18.230 --> 01:01:21.810
PROFESSOR: He created suspense
by taking a risk.

01:01:21.810 --> 01:01:26.420
So there was actually tension,
not this kind of tension, but

01:01:26.420 --> 01:01:29.350
the good kind attention where
people were involved in

01:01:29.350 --> 01:01:30.070
interested.

01:01:30.070 --> 01:01:32.720
Because he redid the experiment,
and it could have

01:01:32.720 --> 01:01:34.910
come out not quite right.

01:01:34.910 --> 01:01:37.090
And amazingly, it did
come out right.

01:01:37.090 --> 01:01:39.670
And when it does, then the point
he's trying to make it

01:01:39.670 --> 01:01:43.700
even more strongly reinforced
about physics works.

01:01:43.700 --> 01:01:44.720
And that was his goal.

01:01:44.720 --> 01:01:47.900
That was one of his overall
goals for the implicit.

01:01:47.900 --> 01:01:50.690
I don't know if he ever stated
it, but one of his implicit

01:01:50.690 --> 01:01:53.030
goals, you can see, is
to convince people

01:01:53.030 --> 01:01:54.240
that physics works.

01:01:54.240 --> 01:01:56.170
It's a way of understanding
the world.

01:01:56.170 --> 01:01:59.040
And if you really believe that,
well, you should be

01:01:59.040 --> 01:02:00.370
willing to put your money
where your mouth

01:02:00.370 --> 01:02:02.750
is and do it yourself.

01:02:02.750 --> 01:02:04.640
There's an another famous
experiment--

01:02:04.640 --> 01:02:08.380
I don't know if it's in
Lewin's lectures--

01:02:08.380 --> 01:02:12.510
where you want to show that
energy is conserved.

01:02:12.510 --> 01:02:17.680
And the way you measure energy
conservation is how far a

01:02:17.680 --> 01:02:19.300
pendulum swings.

01:02:19.300 --> 01:02:21.260
So now the way you do the
experiment, you have some

01:02:21.260 --> 01:02:23.680
giant pendulum with a bowling
ball or a cannon ball at the

01:02:23.680 --> 01:02:26.140
end hanging from the top of
the physics lecture hall,

01:02:26.140 --> 01:02:27.510
which is about this high.

01:02:27.510 --> 01:02:29.520
And you release it from
your nose, and

01:02:29.520 --> 01:02:31.240
you just stand there.

01:02:31.240 --> 01:02:34.070
So if energy's really conserved,
it's going to come

01:02:34.070 --> 01:02:38.100
just to where you released it
and no farther, which is good

01:02:38.100 --> 01:02:39.180
because your nose
is right there.

01:02:39.180 --> 01:02:40.490
A little farther would hurt.

01:02:40.490 --> 01:02:42.350
The problem--

01:02:42.350 --> 01:02:44.100
this still doesn't show physics
doesn't work, but it

01:02:44.100 --> 01:02:44.960
looks like it--

01:02:44.960 --> 01:02:48.380
is that it's so tempting to give
it a little push when you

01:02:48.380 --> 01:02:50.370
release it.

01:02:50.370 --> 01:02:54.060
And it's just hard not to do,
because whenever you let go of

01:02:54.060 --> 01:02:55.800
things, you push a ball,
you throw something

01:02:55.800 --> 01:02:56.590
in the laundry basket.

01:02:56.590 --> 01:02:58.110
So now you give it
a little bit of

01:02:58.110 --> 01:02:59.910
push, and physics works.

01:02:59.910 --> 01:03:03.940
So it comes back with exactly
the same push, which wouldn't

01:03:03.940 --> 01:03:06.350
be a problem if it was a
wiffleball or a tennis ball.

01:03:06.350 --> 01:03:08.340
But because it's a giant cannon
ball and at the other

01:03:08.340 --> 01:03:11.040
end of it's your nose,
it gives you a nice

01:03:11.040 --> 01:03:12.610
crunch right there.

01:03:15.690 --> 01:03:17.940
I would only do that expect if
I'd practiced it and make sure

01:03:17.940 --> 01:03:18.890
I didn't push it.

01:03:18.890 --> 01:03:24.110
But even if you do push it, it
too shows physics works.

01:03:24.110 --> 01:03:28.000
But yeah, he created suspense.

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:28.840
Yes.

01:03:28.840 --> 01:03:31.108
AUDIENCE: So how can people do
this in other disciplines?

01:03:31.108 --> 01:03:33.418
In physics, you have weights
and swinging

01:03:33.418 --> 01:03:36.140
pendulums and blocks.

01:03:36.140 --> 01:03:37.790
PROFESSOR: How can you do
it in other fields?

01:03:37.790 --> 01:03:39.990
Yeah, it's a good question.

01:03:39.990 --> 01:03:41.720
If you remember, the
wood blocks--

01:03:41.720 --> 01:03:43.770
this is physics, mechanical
engineering--

01:03:43.770 --> 01:03:46.080
there was also suspense.

01:03:46.080 --> 01:03:54.140
Because when I tap this one,
and then everyone was dead

01:03:54.140 --> 01:03:58.030
silent before we tapped
this one--

01:03:58.030 --> 01:04:01.030
just for review--

01:04:01.030 --> 01:04:02.270
because everyone
wanted to know.

01:04:02.270 --> 01:04:04.850
So suspense was created.

01:04:04.850 --> 01:04:08.600
And it's just like any sort of
magic trick or performance.

01:04:11.170 --> 01:04:12.730
You have to prepare it.

01:04:12.730 --> 01:04:15.518
So it doesn't have to be that
you bring something in.

01:04:18.020 --> 01:04:18.860
It helps.

01:04:18.860 --> 01:04:22.940
But, let's see, what else
could you do it in?

01:04:22.940 --> 01:04:24.620
Chemistry.

01:04:24.620 --> 01:04:25.950
In chemistry--

01:04:25.950 --> 01:04:27.440
it helps to bring stuff
in, no question-- you

01:04:27.440 --> 01:04:28.450
could bring in chemicals.

01:04:28.450 --> 01:04:30.850
What do you think is going to
happen when I mix these two?

01:04:30.850 --> 01:04:31.970
Well, what do we know
about this?

01:04:31.970 --> 01:04:33.490
What do we know about this?

01:04:33.490 --> 01:04:36.354
What's going to happen when I
drop a ball through this?

01:04:36.354 --> 01:04:37.740
Is this viscous?

01:04:37.740 --> 01:04:38.360
Is it not?

01:04:38.360 --> 01:04:39.920
What clues did you have?

01:04:39.920 --> 01:04:40.980
OK.

01:04:40.980 --> 01:04:42.320
Let's see if now that's
consistent with

01:04:42.320 --> 01:04:43.360
how the thing behaves.

01:04:43.360 --> 01:04:45.350
So it doesn't have to
be pure physics.

01:04:45.350 --> 01:04:48.470
Though it does help to bring
things in, and so you do want

01:04:48.470 --> 01:04:55.520
to make everything you have as
visceral and as visualizable

01:04:55.520 --> 01:04:56.590
as possible.

01:04:56.590 --> 01:05:00.640
So that is a general
transferable principal.

01:05:00.640 --> 01:05:07.490
Let me write down four general
principles that you can use in

01:05:07.490 --> 01:05:11.180
all lecture performance,
which is basically

01:05:11.180 --> 01:05:12.670
everything you said here.

01:05:32.020 --> 01:05:34.580
The first one I'm going to write
down is very neglected,

01:05:34.580 --> 01:05:36.290
but you've just mentioned
it, which is the

01:05:36.290 --> 01:05:37.540
suspense and the timing.

01:05:41.540 --> 01:05:45.280
If you want evidence that timing
really matters, just go

01:05:45.280 --> 01:05:49.550
watch Romeo and Juliet again,
or read Romeo and Juliet.

01:05:49.550 --> 01:05:51.830
Just because they were slightly
off in their timing,

01:05:51.830 --> 01:05:53.190
they all committed suicide,
basically.

01:05:58.090 --> 01:06:00.490
That's probably the very, very,
very, very CliffsNotes

01:06:00.490 --> 01:06:01.740
plot summary.

01:06:05.380 --> 01:06:08.090
And another part about timing,
if you want more evidence that

01:06:08.090 --> 01:06:12.170
timing really matters, try
telling a joke and tell the

01:06:12.170 --> 01:06:15.130
punchline first.

01:06:15.130 --> 01:06:16.970
See how well that does.

01:06:16.970 --> 01:06:20.260
And even a small example of
that, for stories too.

01:06:20.260 --> 01:06:23.500
Stories, you want to tell the
important part later, and you

01:06:23.500 --> 01:06:25.540
want to give the introduction
first.

01:06:25.540 --> 01:06:29.060
Again, remember the sentence
structure here, which is that

01:06:29.060 --> 01:06:32.770
the thing with emphasis comes
right at the end.

01:06:32.770 --> 01:06:34.940
If the thing you want to
emphasize happened at the

01:06:34.940 --> 01:06:37.790
beginning, then your
timing is off, and

01:06:37.790 --> 01:06:38.850
things will fall flat.

01:06:38.850 --> 01:06:39.220
Yes.

01:06:39.220 --> 01:06:39.671
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:06:39.671 --> 01:06:42.830
But that's exactly contradictory
to the way some

01:06:42.830 --> 01:06:48.760
people want their information
laid out, which is tell me the

01:06:48.760 --> 01:06:51.700
most important thing, and then
back up with all the details.

01:06:51.700 --> 01:06:53.900
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:06:53.900 --> 01:06:54.120
OK.

01:06:54.120 --> 01:06:56.940
So that's a good comment, which
is that it's opposite of

01:06:56.940 --> 01:06:58.190
how people say they
want things.

01:06:58.190 --> 01:06:59.860
They want the most important
stuff first

01:06:59.860 --> 01:07:01.800
and then the details.

01:07:01.800 --> 01:07:06.670
The way I square that circle is
I don't want to give away

01:07:06.670 --> 01:07:07.920
punchlines.

01:07:09.950 --> 01:07:10.770
Oh, those are gone.

01:07:10.770 --> 01:07:13.400
So suppose I'm starting a new
unit, and we're going to do a

01:07:13.400 --> 01:07:16.120
unit on extreme cases.

01:07:16.120 --> 01:07:19.150
I don't want to give away the
punchline, which is, oh, this

01:07:19.150 --> 01:07:21.780
problem is hard until you
use extreme cases.

01:07:21.780 --> 01:07:24.665
So I say, forget the
organization of the course

01:07:24.665 --> 01:07:27.150
that I told you about before,
and we're just going to do an

01:07:27.150 --> 01:07:28.550
example and discuss it.

01:07:28.550 --> 01:07:31.020
Then we're going to look at what
makes it really easy, and

01:07:31.020 --> 01:07:34.180
then the punchline
is extreme cases.

01:07:34.180 --> 01:07:34.640
OK.

01:07:34.640 --> 01:07:37.630
Now that we know the punchline,
because we've done

01:07:37.630 --> 01:07:40.750
the example, now I'm very happy
to say extreme cases.

01:07:40.750 --> 01:07:42.280
Let's use extreme cases here.

01:07:42.280 --> 01:07:45.310
And this whole unit is going
to be about extreme cases.

01:07:45.310 --> 01:07:47.380
So now people still have the
structure, but the very

01:07:47.380 --> 01:07:49.650
beginning of it, they're
a little confused.

01:07:49.650 --> 01:07:51.470
And I like the confusion.

01:07:51.470 --> 01:07:54.870
So that's part of this.

01:07:54.870 --> 01:07:58.050
In a play or in a movie, or you
go to a movie, you're not

01:07:58.050 --> 01:07:59.920
even sure who are the
main characters and

01:07:59.920 --> 01:08:00.900
what are they up to.

01:08:00.900 --> 01:08:04.080
And then it comes into focus
soon but not right away.

01:08:04.080 --> 01:08:05.410
And part of that is
to draw you in.

01:08:08.330 --> 01:08:09.040
Yeah.

01:08:09.040 --> 01:08:11.950
I wouldn't begin a lecture by
telling people everything that

01:08:11.950 --> 01:08:16.680
they need to know, because
that's spoiling the timing.

01:08:16.680 --> 01:08:19.569
The beginning of the lecture is
this kind of sacred moment

01:08:19.569 --> 01:08:22.430
when you want to draw everybody
into the lecture.

01:08:25.540 --> 01:08:28.590
And the beginning of a course
is doubly that much.

01:08:28.590 --> 01:08:32.689
You want to draw people in, not
tell them, oh, yeah, here

01:08:32.689 --> 01:08:35.520
are the rules on homework
collaboration and blah, blah,

01:08:35.520 --> 01:08:37.210
blah, blah.

01:08:37.210 --> 01:08:39.425
You want to emphasize the
important things first, and

01:08:39.425 --> 01:08:42.380
you want to use this to pull
people in so that you can come

01:08:42.380 --> 01:08:43.340
to a punchline.

01:08:43.340 --> 01:08:45.100
The punchline doesn't have to
be way at the end of the

01:08:45.100 --> 01:08:46.460
lecture or the end
of the course.

01:08:46.460 --> 01:08:49.029
It can be soon, and you can have
a lot of soon punchlines.

01:08:49.029 --> 01:08:51.300
But for each one, you
need to build to it.

01:08:51.300 --> 01:08:51.649
Yes.

01:08:51.649 --> 01:08:53.050
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:08:53.050 --> 01:08:56.786
When I did my referencing thing,
