01:13:42.630 --> 01:13:44.190
What is the Berkeley
Physics Course?

01:13:44.190 --> 01:13:46.730
The Berkeley Physics Course--

01:13:46.730 --> 01:13:49.860
This is interesting, because in
the '60s there was a whole

01:13:49.860 --> 01:13:51.930
bunch of change.

01:13:51.930 --> 01:13:56.110
It was change in political
systems and protests and legal

01:13:56.110 --> 01:13:58.730
systems, the Civil Rights Act.

01:13:58.730 --> 01:14:00.620
And there was also change
in education.

01:14:00.620 --> 01:14:04.660
And that's probably not
coincidence, that both changes

01:14:04.660 --> 01:14:06.710
were coupled or happened
together.

01:14:06.710 --> 01:14:08.550
There was the rise of the
Free School Movement.

01:14:08.550 --> 01:14:11.230
There was also, in the
university level, lots of

01:14:11.230 --> 01:14:13.270
different new curricula
started.

01:14:13.270 --> 01:14:16.340
The Feynman Lectures on physics
are a famous one that

01:14:16.340 --> 01:14:18.870
happened way over on
the other side of

01:14:18.870 --> 01:14:20.560
the country and Caltech.

01:14:20.560 --> 01:14:23.780
And the Berkeley Physics Course
happened also on the

01:14:23.780 --> 01:14:26.540
other side of the country.

01:14:26.540 --> 01:14:27.710
There are several
volumes in it.

01:14:27.710 --> 01:14:30.220
Probably the best known
is Ed Purcell's

01:14:30.220 --> 01:14:32.250
Electricity and Magnetism.

01:14:32.250 --> 01:14:34.510
That's one of the classics of
the Berkeley Physics Course.

01:14:34.510 --> 01:14:37.320
There's a less well-known
volume, which is, I think,

01:14:37.320 --> 01:14:39.265
even better, which is
by Frank Crawford,

01:14:39.265 --> 01:14:41.670
and it's called Waves.

01:14:41.670 --> 01:14:44.980
The edition I have came in the
back with a whole bunch of

01:14:44.980 --> 01:14:48.500
polarizers and toys you could
use to actually do home

01:14:48.500 --> 01:14:49.100
experiments.

01:14:49.100 --> 01:14:50.790
And at the end of every chapter,
there are home

01:14:50.790 --> 01:14:51.350
experiments.

01:14:51.350 --> 01:14:54.430
I think they're called "Kitchen
Sink Experiments, and

01:14:54.430 --> 01:14:57.630
there were toys in the back in
the little pocket that you

01:14:57.630 --> 01:14:58.500
could use for it.

01:14:58.500 --> 01:15:01.330
So if you find a used copy,
those toys might not be there,

01:15:01.330 --> 01:15:03.130
but the book is still
wonderful.

01:15:03.130 --> 01:15:05.930
So those were two pieces of the
Berkeley Physics Course,

01:15:05.930 --> 01:15:07.340
and they were about
six volumes.

01:15:07.340 --> 01:15:09.640
And MIT had a whole set
of books as well, I

01:15:09.640 --> 01:15:11.150
think by Tony French.

01:15:11.150 --> 01:15:14.160
So it was a whole time of
ferment, and lots of changes

01:15:14.160 --> 01:15:17.120
happened, many of them good.

01:15:17.120 --> 01:15:20.080
OK.

01:15:20.080 --> 01:15:22.570
How can you apply these lecture
techniques that we

01:15:22.570 --> 01:15:23.795
talked about last time
to laboratory

01:15:23.795 --> 01:15:25.130
or practical courses?

01:15:25.130 --> 01:15:27.030
This is actually an important
topic, because many

01:15:27.030 --> 01:15:29.150
of us will do that?

01:15:29.150 --> 01:15:31.850
What's the right balance between
teaching and lecturing

01:15:31.850 --> 01:15:34.920
and allowing students to solve
the lab problems on their own,

01:15:34.920 --> 01:15:36.540
in other words, giving them
enough rope to hang

01:15:36.540 --> 01:15:38.000
themselves?

01:15:38.000 --> 01:15:39.110
Yeah.

01:15:39.110 --> 01:15:40.060
You do want to do that.

01:15:40.060 --> 01:15:43.240
You want to give people enough
rope, but you also want to

01:15:43.240 --> 01:15:45.890
guide them, because you do
know more than them.

01:15:45.890 --> 01:15:49.300
So I don't look at laboratory
teaching, practical teaching

01:15:49.300 --> 01:15:51.100
as that different than
lecture teaching.

01:15:51.100 --> 01:15:53.680
In some ways, it's easier,
because one of the goals in

01:15:53.680 --> 01:15:56.890
lecture teaching is to show
people that all the theory

01:15:56.890 --> 01:15:59.830
you're talking about actually
has any relevance at all.

01:15:59.830 --> 01:16:02.570
And you have to try to work hard
to bring stuff into the

01:16:02.570 --> 01:16:04.640
classroom and really show, yeah,
look this really means

01:16:04.640 --> 01:16:08.770
something, the way Walter Lewin
stood on the pendulum or

01:16:08.770 --> 01:16:11.540
sat on the pendulum himself and
was the pendulum to really

01:16:11.540 --> 01:16:14.480
show, yes, this applies here.

01:16:14.480 --> 01:16:17.600
In a laboratory practical class,
if the practicals are

01:16:17.600 --> 01:16:22.210
at all interesting, that's
automatically done for you.

01:16:22.210 --> 01:16:26.310
The last practical class I
taught was the electronics

01:16:26.310 --> 01:16:29.180
practical for physics majors.

01:16:29.180 --> 01:16:32.750
At the end, they built an AM
radio, a crystal radio.

01:16:32.750 --> 01:16:36.440
So that actually had a nice
finale, and experiments before

01:16:36.440 --> 01:16:39.150
that built up to it.

01:16:39.150 --> 01:16:42.440
The relevance was already done
for me, but the problems the

01:16:42.440 --> 01:16:45.390
students had were the same
as in regular lecture.

01:16:45.390 --> 01:16:46.830
They didn't understand
the concepts.

01:16:46.830 --> 01:16:49.230
For example, what does
a capacitor do?

01:16:49.230 --> 01:16:50.330
What does an inductor do?

01:16:50.330 --> 01:16:51.320
How do they work together?

01:16:51.320 --> 01:16:52.440
What is resonance?

01:16:52.440 --> 01:16:54.900
So what I did for them is
I gave them short little

01:16:54.900 --> 01:16:58.410
mini-lectures, two minutes three
minutes on a conceptual

01:16:58.410 --> 01:17:00.535
question, and then sent
them off working.

01:17:03.780 --> 01:17:05.730
Some of the other problems they
had were, for example,

01:17:05.730 --> 01:17:08.950
they were really scared
of oscilloscopes.

01:17:08.950 --> 01:17:09.960
They just got to the
oscilloscope, and they

01:17:09.960 --> 01:17:12.070
thought, what the hell do
I do with this thing?

01:17:12.070 --> 01:17:15.200
So do I used an exercise that
was done to me when I took the

01:17:15.200 --> 01:17:17.830
same class as an undergraduate,
which was in

01:17:17.830 --> 01:17:23.050
your laboratory pair one person
turns around and the

01:17:23.050 --> 01:17:26.380
other person randomizes the
oscilloscope settings.

01:17:26.380 --> 01:17:29.595
They just turn all of dials to
some random setting, and then

01:17:29.595 --> 01:17:32.020
the first person has to turn
back and try to get some

01:17:32.020 --> 01:17:33.450
signal on the screen.

01:17:33.450 --> 01:17:36.500
So they have to figure out, OK,
this voltage setting is

01:17:36.500 --> 01:17:38.930
crazy and get it back
to a setting.

01:17:38.930 --> 01:17:41.030
And once you do that, you're
no longer afraid of the

01:17:41.030 --> 01:17:41.910
oscilloscope.

01:17:41.910 --> 01:17:45.290
Again, you can do in
class problems that

01:17:45.290 --> 01:17:46.700
people work on together.

01:17:46.700 --> 01:17:49.260
You can give short little
conceptual questions.

01:17:49.260 --> 01:17:52.240
So in a way, laboratory teaching
isn't that different,

01:17:52.240 --> 01:17:56.220
provided that the laboratory
isn't just a cookbook in the

01:17:56.220 --> 01:17:58.780
sense that, OK, do this, now
measure that, now measure

01:17:58.780 --> 01:18:00.690
that, now measure that,
now measure that.

01:18:00.690 --> 01:18:03.080
OK, write it all
in your report.

01:18:03.080 --> 01:18:06.290
That's like lecturing just by
saying now copy this down, now

01:18:06.290 --> 01:18:07.960
copy that down, now
copy that down.

01:18:07.960 --> 01:18:10.230
So if you get away from that
in lecturing and that in

01:18:10.230 --> 01:18:13.810
practical, then you get to the
similarities between the two,

01:18:13.810 --> 01:18:16.730
and you can apply pretty much
every lesson from here.

01:18:19.510 --> 01:18:20.760
OK.

01:18:22.800 --> 01:18:23.305
Oh, yeah.

01:18:23.305 --> 01:18:24.500
Many of you pointed this out.

01:18:24.500 --> 01:18:27.300
The distillation of examples
into principles that we did.

01:18:27.300 --> 01:18:30.500
So we looked at Walter Lewin's
lecture number 10, and then we

01:18:30.500 --> 01:18:33.620
distilled from our discussion
various principles of

01:18:33.620 --> 01:18:35.390
lecturing and performing.

01:18:35.390 --> 01:18:36.490
And many of you said,
oh, yeah, that

01:18:36.490 --> 01:18:38.360
should have gone longer.

01:18:38.360 --> 01:18:40.480
You liked the principles, but
we should have done that for

01:18:40.480 --> 01:18:42.150
longer, which I think
is a great sign.

01:18:42.150 --> 01:18:44.260
I think it's good that you guys
are figuring out what

01:18:44.260 --> 01:18:44.960
could be improved.

01:18:44.960 --> 01:18:46.030
And I agree with you.

01:18:46.030 --> 01:18:49.210
I just got so carried away
with all the interesting

01:18:49.210 --> 01:18:52.200
things you were finding that I
didn't allocate enough time

01:18:52.200 --> 01:18:53.210
for the principles.

01:18:53.210 --> 01:18:57.180
So in my next life.

01:18:57.180 --> 01:19:00.740
But also, the point is everyone
did appreciate having

01:19:00.740 --> 01:19:03.610
principles, so that's something
to transfer for your

01:19:03.610 --> 01:19:05.650
own teaching.

01:19:05.650 --> 01:19:06.290
OK.

01:19:06.290 --> 01:19:09.290
Let's see.

01:19:09.290 --> 01:19:11.870
What kind of interactive
examples and demos can you do

01:19:11.870 --> 01:19:13.120
for a math class?

01:19:15.710 --> 01:19:18.249
I brought an example.

01:19:18.249 --> 01:19:20.790
They're in here.

01:19:20.790 --> 01:19:24.000
This was actually an example
I did last week in my

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:25.310
approximation class.

01:19:25.310 --> 01:19:28.000
And I enjoyed it so
much I thought I'd

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:29.250
show it to you too.

01:19:35.350 --> 01:19:43.680
The principal I was teaching
was the principle of easy

01:19:43.680 --> 01:19:46.480
cases, also known as extreme
cases often.

01:19:46.480 --> 01:19:48.690
But I like this name better.

01:19:48.690 --> 01:19:52.220
And then I wanted to show that
this principle applies across

01:19:52.220 --> 01:19:52.950
all kinds of areas.

01:19:52.950 --> 01:19:53.810
You can use it in math.

01:19:53.810 --> 01:19:54.590
You can use it in physics.

01:19:54.590 --> 01:19:56.580
You can use it in engineering.

01:19:56.580 --> 01:19:58.840
And what we were trying
to derive is

01:19:58.840 --> 01:20:00.948
the volume of a pyramid.

01:20:00.948 --> 01:20:02.990
So the original problem
was this.

01:20:06.480 --> 01:20:10.290
You take a pyramid with a square
base, and then you lop

01:20:10.290 --> 01:20:12.860
off some piece of the top.

01:20:12.860 --> 01:20:22.140
So the pyramid is B by B on the
base and A by A square on

01:20:22.140 --> 01:20:23.950
the top, and it has height h.

01:20:26.480 --> 01:20:29.070
So what's the volume
of that thing?

01:20:29.070 --> 01:20:32.990
Well, you can guess a lot
of it from easy cases.

01:20:32.990 --> 01:20:34.140
I won't go through
all of that.

01:20:34.140 --> 01:20:36.970
But at some point, you need to
work out in part of this guess

01:20:36.970 --> 01:20:40.180
the easy cases, use the easy
case that A equals 0.

01:20:40.180 --> 01:20:43.070
In other words, you just have a
regular square pyramid, like

01:20:43.070 --> 01:20:45.725
one of the Egyptian
pyramids of Gaza.

01:20:45.725 --> 01:20:46.010
Giza?

01:20:46.010 --> 01:20:47.900
Giza, maybe.

01:20:47.900 --> 01:20:49.150
So then what's the volume?

01:21:01.980 --> 01:21:02.310
OK.

01:21:02.310 --> 01:21:07.830
Well, volume's going to be
proportional to the height.

01:21:07.830 --> 01:21:11.815
And then, it's got to have two
more lengths here, so it's got

01:21:11.815 --> 01:21:12.830
to have B squared here.

01:21:12.830 --> 01:21:13.830
There's no A left.

01:21:13.830 --> 01:21:15.080
But then what goes here?

01:21:19.200 --> 01:21:20.630
What's the constant?

01:21:20.630 --> 01:21:23.180
Well, this is actually
where you can, yet

01:21:23.180 --> 01:21:26.060
again, use easy cases.

01:21:26.060 --> 01:21:32.970
So if you could find a special
pyramid that could be combined

01:21:32.970 --> 01:21:36.300
into a shape whose volume you
know, then you could actually

01:21:36.300 --> 01:21:37.770
figure out this constant.

01:21:37.770 --> 01:21:39.590
Because you don't know the
volume of one pyramid, but if

01:21:39.590 --> 01:21:42.590
you could replicate it and then
assemble them into a nice

01:21:42.590 --> 01:21:45.610
shape, you're home free.

01:21:45.610 --> 01:21:48.580
What nice shape could
make this into?

01:21:48.580 --> 01:21:52.520
And what pyramid shape do you
need to be able to do that?

01:21:52.520 --> 01:21:54.140
So take a minute and
think about that.

01:21:57.260 --> 01:21:59.480
Anyone have an idea?

01:21:59.480 --> 01:22:01.410
What shape would you
like to make?

01:22:01.410 --> 01:22:04.290
AUDIENCE: Could you first make
a rectangular cube and then

01:22:04.290 --> 01:22:06.220
cut it into six pieces?

01:22:06.220 --> 01:22:06.420
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:22:06.420 --> 01:22:09.460
So you want to make a cube.

01:22:09.460 --> 01:22:11.170
Let's talk about how you're
going to make this cube.

01:22:11.170 --> 01:22:13.720
You'd like to make the cube.

01:22:13.720 --> 01:22:17.000
Now what part of the pyramid
is going to become

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:17.990
the face of the cube?

01:22:17.990 --> 01:22:20.230
Well, you have a square
base, right?

01:22:20.230 --> 01:22:23.220
So it seems reasonable to expect
that each pyramid's

01:22:23.220 --> 01:22:25.260
going to provide one
face the cube.

01:22:25.260 --> 01:22:28.300
So you need six pyramids
to make this cube.

01:22:28.300 --> 01:22:31.020
Well, what shape should the
pyramid have so that you can

01:22:31.020 --> 01:22:32.666
fit them into a cube?

01:22:32.666 --> 01:22:33.916
Hmm.

01:22:38.940 --> 01:22:40.550
How about that shape?

01:22:40.550 --> 01:22:43.410
So what's special about
that shape?

01:22:43.410 --> 01:22:46.440
I'll put one here, and here's
another one of them.

01:22:49.800 --> 01:22:51.240
Put that there.

01:22:55.100 --> 01:22:56.350
And here's another one.

01:23:08.330 --> 01:23:09.100
OK.

01:23:09.100 --> 01:23:10.170
So here we go.

01:23:10.170 --> 01:23:12.910
Here's a cube with six
of those pyramids.

01:23:12.910 --> 01:23:16.431
So what's special about the
shape of the pyramid?

01:23:16.431 --> 01:23:18.350
What do you have to set in it?

01:23:18.350 --> 01:23:18.750
Yeah.

01:23:18.750 --> 01:23:21.940
AUDIENCE: The height is
half of the base line.

01:23:21.940 --> 01:23:22.210
PROFESSOR: OK.

01:23:22.210 --> 01:23:23.220
The height is half the base.

01:23:23.220 --> 01:23:23.870
How do you know that?

01:23:23.870 --> 01:23:28.400
AUDIENCE: Because the tips of
the pyramids are [INAUDIBLE].

01:23:28.400 --> 01:23:28.750
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:23:28.750 --> 01:23:30.440
So the tips touch like this.

01:23:30.440 --> 01:23:35.550
And this width has to equal
either side of the square.

01:23:35.550 --> 01:23:48.520
That means, let's say, if h
equals 1 and B equals 2, six

01:23:48.520 --> 01:23:50.395
times the volume is equal
to the volume of the

01:23:50.395 --> 01:23:52.240
cube, which is 8.

01:23:52.240 --> 01:23:56.370
So the volume of one pyramid
is 8/6 or 4/3.

01:23:56.370 --> 01:24:02.020
h times b squared is 4, so you
have to divide it by 3, and

01:24:02.020 --> 01:24:03.220
you're home free.

01:24:03.220 --> 01:24:06.550
So there's an example of a
demonstration in math class

01:24:06.550 --> 01:24:08.410
that you can use.

01:24:08.410 --> 01:24:14.340
Now the point of it is that it's
possible to imagine it in

01:24:14.340 --> 01:24:17.230
your head, but it is actually
useful to see these things

01:24:17.230 --> 01:24:20.620
built into a cube.

01:24:20.620 --> 01:24:23.140
So even in math class you
can do demonstrations.

01:24:30.220 --> 01:24:32.350
What's my blackboard
philosophy?

01:24:32.350 --> 01:24:35.130
I write big and sometimes place
things fairly randomly.

01:24:35.130 --> 01:24:37.050
Is there a specific
reason for this?

01:24:37.050 --> 01:24:39.760
But I like what you
write down.

01:24:39.760 --> 01:24:40.030
Yeah.

01:24:40.030 --> 01:24:42.470
My blackboard philosophy
is not ideal,

01:24:42.470 --> 01:24:44.880
because of exactly that.

01:24:44.880 --> 01:24:47.870
I write large, which is good,
but I do place things kind of

01:24:47.870 --> 01:24:48.990
randomly sometimes.

01:24:48.990 --> 01:24:53.870
And that's not ideal, so
I try to improve that.

01:24:53.870 --> 01:24:57.330
I don't necessarily have
a reason for that.

01:24:57.330 --> 01:25:00.700
Don't actually copy that part
of my blackboard style.

01:25:00.700 --> 01:25:02.650
But it's good that you're
observing that and trying to

01:25:02.650 --> 01:25:04.710
criticize it.

01:25:04.710 --> 01:25:05.550
OK.

01:25:05.550 --> 01:25:06.750
Let's see.

01:25:06.750 --> 01:25:08.840
How to practice blackboard
work.

01:25:08.840 --> 01:25:10.240
We'll talk about that
more today.

01:25:10.240 --> 01:25:13.990
But the basic simplest way that
I've found is at the end

01:25:13.990 --> 01:25:17.080
of your session you just go to
the back of the room and look

01:25:17.080 --> 01:25:21.310
at the blackboard and you just
see was it organized, did it

01:25:21.310 --> 01:25:24.110
make sense, did I write a bunch
of stuff in between, and

01:25:24.110 --> 01:25:26.520
just take a few notes
down on that.

01:25:26.520 --> 01:25:28.650
And then you'll automatically
be getting feedback that you

01:25:28.650 --> 01:25:30.490
can use to improve your
blackboard work.

01:25:35.530 --> 01:25:36.110
Oh, yeah.

01:25:36.110 --> 01:25:39.010
Several people pointed out
they watched a different

01:25:39.010 --> 01:25:41.410
lecture than Walter Lewin's
Lecture 10, because I said,

01:25:41.410 --> 01:25:43.190
oh, watch that one
or another one.

01:25:43.190 --> 01:25:45.470
So next year, I actually am
going to ask everyone to watch

01:25:45.470 --> 01:25:47.420
the same lecture, Lecture 10.

01:25:47.420 --> 01:25:48.670
That's a good suggestion.

01:25:51.090 --> 01:25:53.330
OK.

01:25:53.330 --> 01:25:55.090
We talked about that.

01:25:59.350 --> 01:26:02.260
Oh, yeah, if you're an excellent
lecturer and you are

01:26:02.260 --> 01:26:04.960
aware of the common problems,
because you've taught the

01:26:04.960 --> 01:26:07.430
course many times before, and
you try to address all the

01:26:07.430 --> 01:26:12.280
confusing parts, can you get
away with not allowing

01:26:12.280 --> 01:26:15.360
students to ask questions in
class and not asking students

01:26:15.360 --> 01:26:17.000
questions yourself?

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:19.030
That's a very interesting
question.

01:26:19.030 --> 01:26:21.620
Basically, can you move away
from the interactive model

01:26:21.620 --> 01:26:24.310
I've been describing and
recommending once you've done

01:26:24.310 --> 01:26:25.620
it enough and you know
where the students'

01:26:25.620 --> 01:26:27.470
misconceptions are.

01:26:27.470 --> 01:26:29.590
I thought about that, and
the answer is really no.

01:26:29.590 --> 01:26:35.860
Because then you're reverting
back to telling.

01:26:35.860 --> 01:26:38.300
Now you're telling them things
they really do need to know.

01:26:38.300 --> 01:26:40.640
So instead of telling them a big
long song and dance about

01:26:40.640 --> 01:26:43.680
the Atwood machine, which they
don't really need to know,

01:26:43.680 --> 01:26:45.440
you're telling them about
their misconceptions

01:26:45.440 --> 01:26:46.890
about F equals ma.

01:26:46.890 --> 01:26:50.200
But the problem is just telling
them that F equals ma,

01:26:50.200 --> 01:26:52.990
F equals mv, doesn't help
them realize that.

01:26:52.990 --> 01:26:55.720
They really have to have some
kind of cognitive conflict and

01:26:55.720 --> 01:26:56.820
struggle with it.

01:26:56.820 --> 01:27:02.210
So questioning, either you
question them or them asking

01:27:02.210 --> 01:27:04.980
questions of you and formulating
questions, is

01:27:04.980 --> 01:27:07.390
really about the only way to get
them to struggle with it.

01:27:07.390 --> 01:27:09.770
Even then, you still
have to do it.

01:27:09.770 --> 01:27:12.230
And the experience you have from
teaching it many times

01:27:12.230 --> 01:27:14.700
means you'll be doing questions
about useful,

01:27:14.700 --> 01:27:16.390
important material.

01:27:16.390 --> 01:27:20.255
That was quite an interesting
question.

01:27:20.255 --> 01:27:21.505
OK.

01:27:27.340 --> 01:27:29.820
What do I think of group
assignments, balancing the

01:27:29.820 --> 01:27:34.030
advantages of collaboration
with the fact that each

01:27:34.030 --> 01:27:36.280
individual may not encounter
all the topics?

01:27:36.280 --> 01:27:38.900
I generally don't like
them that much.

01:27:38.900 --> 01:27:42.380
I think if you design a course
and you think there's a

01:27:42.380 --> 01:27:45.580
coherent set of material,
everyone really should try to

01:27:45.580 --> 01:27:48.740
master that coherent set of
material and not palm off half

01:27:48.740 --> 01:27:50.320
of it on one person in the
group and the other

01:27:50.320 --> 01:27:51.330
person in the group.

01:27:51.330 --> 01:27:55.010
The extreme of this kind is
the graduate seminar where

01:27:55.010 --> 01:27:58.280
each graduate student gives
a talk on one topic.

01:27:58.280 --> 01:28:00.250
And then they really learn that
one topic, but they don't

01:28:00.250 --> 01:28:03.110
necessarily learn the other
topics very well.

01:28:03.110 --> 01:28:04.840
So I don't like that
very much.

01:28:04.840 --> 01:28:07.460
I think it's better to allow
people to collaborate, but

01:28:07.460 --> 01:28:09.862
make sure everyone does
their own assignment.

01:28:09.862 --> 01:28:12.720
And yeah, collaborate in groups,
by all means, but

01:28:12.720 --> 01:28:14.410
please write up your
own work as well.

01:28:22.490 --> 01:28:25.420
What's the use of experiments
in Walter Lewin's lecture?

01:28:25.420 --> 01:28:28.070
Was it to show the predictive
power physics or its

01:28:28.070 --> 01:28:29.180
experimental character?

01:28:29.180 --> 01:28:29.770
It's not clear.

01:28:29.770 --> 01:28:31.930
And in that case, wouldn't it
be better if the students

01:28:31.930 --> 01:28:35.090
performed the experiments on
their own or in a lab class?

01:28:35.090 --> 01:28:37.130
Aren't these demonstrations a
waste of time that could be

01:28:37.130 --> 01:28:38.710
used to teach more theory?

01:28:38.710 --> 01:28:40.470
And aren't shows more
appropriate for high school

01:28:40.470 --> 01:28:42.500
classes than for
physics at MIT?

01:28:42.500 --> 01:28:46.460
Well, I think, at the time, this
was 1999, there was no

01:28:46.460 --> 01:28:50.820
laboratory with the introductory
physics course.

01:28:50.820 --> 01:28:52.760
I need to get my history right,
but I'm pretty sure

01:28:52.760 --> 01:28:54.160
that's right.

01:28:54.160 --> 01:28:56.650
There was no other way the
students would ever see any

01:28:56.650 --> 01:28:57.720
application.

01:28:57.720 --> 01:29:00.150
But the other main point of it
is that it showed that the

01:29:00.150 --> 01:29:01.850
physics is real.

01:29:01.850 --> 01:29:04.340
Now I think it could be
improved, as you suggested, by

01:29:04.340 --> 01:29:06.270
Lewin asking students
questions about the

01:29:06.270 --> 01:29:09.670
experiments, trying to predict
what would happen beforehand,

01:29:09.670 --> 01:29:10.480
for example.

01:29:10.480 --> 01:29:14.190
But the idea of bringing in
objects is really a sound one.

01:29:14.190 --> 01:29:17.110
I had a teacher at Caltech.

01:29:17.110 --> 01:29:21.480
He taught the waves and the
nonlinear waves course.

01:29:21.480 --> 01:29:26.620
He always used to bring in
a wave guide, which is,

01:29:26.620 --> 01:29:30.400
basically, a piece of metal
in a tube-like shape.

01:29:30.400 --> 01:29:32.800
and he said he always did that
because, otherwise, the

01:29:32.800 --> 01:29:35.560
mathematicians would think it's
just a vessel function,

01:29:35.560 --> 01:29:37.640
because that's how it is
in all the problems.

01:29:37.640 --> 01:29:40.650
You see wave guide, you just
start solving Laplace's

01:29:40.650 --> 01:29:42.250
equation with all these boundary
conditions, you get

01:29:42.250 --> 01:29:43.190
Bessel function.

01:29:43.190 --> 01:29:46.320
And wave guide is just trigger
for do Laplace's equation, get

01:29:46.320 --> 01:29:46.870
Bessel function.

01:29:46.870 --> 01:29:48.390
It has no physical meaning.

01:29:48.390 --> 01:29:50.515
So he would always bring in
the wave guide so that you

01:29:50.515 --> 01:29:52.740
knew that it was a real object
that you were analyzing.

01:29:52.740 --> 01:29:55.400
And so in that way, Lewin, using
the pendulum, showing

01:29:55.400 --> 01:29:59.350
that these things actually
exist, avoids the trap that

01:29:59.350 --> 01:30:02.490
many students fall into, which
is that symbols just have no

01:30:02.490 --> 01:30:03.580
meaning on their own.

01:30:03.580 --> 01:30:06.180
They're just stuff that
goes on on the screen.

01:30:06.180 --> 01:30:10.350
So I think is really important
that he does that.

01:30:10.350 --> 01:30:13.120
OK.

01:30:13.120 --> 01:30:14.590
Working hard versus smart.

01:30:14.590 --> 01:30:16.660
How do you respond to people who
tell you that they worked

01:30:16.660 --> 01:30:18.190
really hard but they
still did poorly?

01:30:21.400 --> 01:30:22.700
I think, basically,
the reason is that

01:30:22.700 --> 01:30:26.100
they didn't work smart.

01:30:26.100 --> 01:30:28.360
So what do students think
working hard means?

01:30:28.360 --> 01:30:30.690
They generally think it means
reading the book over and over

01:30:30.690 --> 01:30:34.500
again or trying really hard
to do the problems but not

01:30:34.500 --> 01:30:37.005
reflecting.

01:30:37.005 --> 01:30:39.430
The equivalent in playing
chess is working hard at

01:30:39.430 --> 01:30:41.420
chess, people think, oh, that
just means playing lots of

01:30:41.420 --> 01:30:41.970
chess games.

01:30:41.970 --> 01:30:44.620
But actually, that doesn't
improve your chess ability.

01:30:44.620 --> 01:30:47.250
You have to analyze your chess
games, reflect on them.

01:30:47.250 --> 01:30:49.730
And that's what we need to
teach students how to do.

01:30:49.730 --> 01:30:51.440
So whenever they do say
that, I say, OK, well,

